Living people]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Croatian male actors]]\n[[Category:Croatian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Croatian male stage actors]]\n[[Category:People from Zenica]]\n[[Category:Bosniaks of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Bosniaks of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Croatian male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bosnian and Croatian television presenter and actor}}\n{{BLP more footnotes|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Tarik Filipovi\u0107\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name =  \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1972|3|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Zenica]], [[Socialist Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina|SR Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| nationality = [[Bosnians|Bosnian]] <br> [[Bosniaks of Croatia|Croatian]] \n| spouse = Lejla \u0160ehovi\u0107\n| occupation  = {{hlist|TV presenter|actor}} \n}}\n\n'''Tarik Filipovi\u0107''' (born 11 March 1972) is a [[Bosnians|Bosnian]] and [[Bosniaks of Croatia|Croatian]] television presenter and actor. He has appeared in over 800 theatre plays since his debut in 1985. He has also been in many films and TV dramas produced throughout the areas of former [[Yugoslavia]].\n\nHe presents quiz shows ''Tko \u017eeli biti milijuna\u0161?'' (Croatia's ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'') on [[Croatian Radiotelevision]], and ''Potjera'' ([[Croatia]]'s ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]'') on [[HRT 1|HRT1]]. In 2001, Filipovi\u0107 starred in ''[[Behind Enemy Lines (2001 film)|Behind Enemy Lines]]'' as a Serbian soldier.\n\n==Personal life==\nFilipovi\u0107 is married to Lejla \u0160ehovi\u0107 with whom he has two sons, Dino and Arman. He is also a supporter of [[NK \u010celik Zenica]] and is a member of the club's administration.\n\nApart from \u010celik, he is an avid supporter of [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb]] and is known for helping Dinamo Zagreb supporters from the [[Dubrava, Zagreb|Dubrava]] neighbourhood in several tight situations.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''Okus limuna''\n|\n| Croatian film\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[The Price of Life (1994 film)|The Price of Life]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Washed Out (film)|Washed Out]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Agonija]]''\n| Inspector\n| Croatian film\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''Srce nije u modi''\n| Hrvatski Vojnik\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''Polagana predaja''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Behind Enemy Lines (2001 film)|2001]]''\n| Serbian soldier\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[24 Hours (2002 film)|24 Hours]]''\n| \u017duti\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Witnesses (2003 film)|Witnesses]]''\n| Javni tu\u017eitelj\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Long Dark Night]]''\n| Joka\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=4|2005\n| ''[[First Class Thieves]]''\n| Narrator\n| Voice\n|-\n| ''[[Two Players from the Bench]]''\n| Anti\u0161a\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Go West (2005 film)|Go West]]''\n| Milan\n| Acting together with [[Rade \u0160erbed\u017eija]]\n|-\n| ''Dobro u\u0161timani mrtvaci''\n| Mario\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Ice Age: The Meltdown]]''\n| Diego\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Ritam \u017eivota''\n| Damir\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2009\n| ''[[Storm (2009 film)|Storm]]''\n| Mladen Banovic\n|\n|-\n| ''U zemlji cudesa''\n| Profesor\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]''\n| Diego\n| Voice\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2014\n| ''Devet polo\u017eaja samo\u0107e''\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''Markov trg''\n| Marko Crnoga\u010da\n| TV movie\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[ZG80]]''\n| Policeman from train #1\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''General''\n| Davor Domazet Lo\u0161o\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''Smogovci''\n| Spasoje\n| Croatian TV-series\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Na\u0161i i va\u0161i]]''\n| prosjak-voditelj\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Na\u0161a mala klinika]]''\n| Harald Schmidt\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[A Mess in the House]]''\n| Tarik Filipovi\u0107\n| 1 episode (acting himself)\n|-\n| 2005\u20132010\n| ''[[Bitange i princeze]]''\n| Teodor \"Teo\" Fri\u0161\u010di\u0107\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Ljubav, navika, panika''\n| Damir\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2006\u20132007\n| ''Kazali\u0161te u ku\u0107i''\n| Karlo Mami\u0107\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Dobre namjere''\n| Ante Liveri\u0107\n| Croatian TV-series\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Tito (2010 TV series)|Tito]]''\n| Tito's Doctor\n| Croatian TV series about [[Josip Broz Tito|Tito's]] life\n|-\n| 2015\u20132016\n| ''[[Lud, zbunjen, normalan]]\n| Avdija\n| 30 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Hilmija's Inn''\n| Sturmbannf\u00fchrer Schiling\n| 25 episodes\n|}\n\n===As television host===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ TV show\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2002\u20132008; 2009\u20132010, 2019\u2013Present\n| ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?|Tko \u017eeli biti milijuna\u0161?]]''\n| Host\n|\n|-\n| 2008\u20132009; 2010\u20132011\n| ''[[1 vs. 100|1 protiv 100]]''\n| Host\n|\n|-\n| 2011\u20132013\n| ''Sve u sedam''\n| Host\n| Croatian version of Succes Verzekerd\n|-\n| 2013\u20132019\n| ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|Potjera]]''\n| Host\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===General references===\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.24sata.hr/show/presretni-tarik-filipovic-super-sam-sad-sam-tata-48428|title=Presretni Tarik Filipovi\u0107: Super sam! Sad sam tata!|language=hr|accessdate=23 April 2020}}\n*{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.index.hr/black/clanak/tarik-filipovic-i-rene-bitorajac-ipak-ne-moraju-platiti-42-milijuna-kuna/725055.aspx |title=Tarik Filipovi\u0107 i Rene Bitorajac ipak ne moraju platiti 4,2 milijuna kuna - black |website=Index.hr |date=2014-01-31 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}\n*{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.index.hr/black/clanak/slavni-hrvati-podijeljeni-oko-ulaska-u-eu-mogli-smo-se-quotsamoubitiquot-i-na-pametniji-nacin/686200.aspx |title=Slavni Hrvati podijeljeni oko ulaska u EU: Mogli smo se \"samoubiti\" i na pametniji na\u010din! - black |website=Index.hr |date=2013-06-30 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1017991|name=Tarik Filipovi\u0107}}\n\n{{The Chase}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Filipovic, Tarik}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Croatian male actors]]\n[[Category:Croatian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Croatian male stage actors]]\n[[Category:People from Zenica]]\n[[Category:Bosniaks of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Bosniaks of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Croatian male actors]]\n", "name_user": "GregorB", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeneral references:Rm stray markup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarik_Filipovi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Edington", "text_new": "{{bots|deny=InternetArchiveBot}}\n{{coord |51|15|50|N|02|08|34|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Edington\n|partof=the [[Norse activity in the British Isles|Viking invasions of England]]\n|date=May 878\n|image=Ethandunmem.jpg\n|image_size=200px\n|caption=Memorial to the ''Battle of Ethandun'' erected in 2000 near the [[hillfort]] of [[Bratton Castle]].<ref>UK Inventory of War Memorials. The Memorial stone plaque reads:{{quote|''TO COMMEMORATE THE BATTLE OF ETHANDUN FOUGHT IN THIS VICINITY MAY 878 AD WHEN KING ALFRED THE GREAT DEFEATED THE VIKING ARMY, GIVING BIRTH TO THE ENGLISH NATIONHOOD. UNVEILED BY THE 7TH MARQUESS OF BATH 5TH NOVEMBER 2000.''}}\nAn additional inscription reads:\n{{quote| ''THIS STONE, PRESENTED BY F. SWANTON AND SONS, NORTH FARM, WEST OVERTON, IS A SARSEN STONE SIMILAR TO THOSE AT KINGSTON DEVERILL, THE AREA WHERE KING ALFRED RALLIED SAXON LEVIES FROM HAMPSHIRE, WILTSHIRE AND SOMERSET TO MARCH AGAINST GUTHRUM'S VIKING ARMY BASED AT CHIPPENHAM.''}}</ref>\n|place= Probably [[Edington, Wiltshire|Edington]], Wiltshire\n|casus=\n|territory=\n|result=Decisive West Saxon victory\n|combatant1= [[Wessex|West Saxons]]\n|combatant2= [[Danelaw]] [[Vikings]]\n|commander1=[[Alfred the Great]]\n|commander2=[[Guthrum the Old]]\n|strength1=unknown\n|strength2=unknown\n|casualties1=unknown\n|casualties2=unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Viking invasions of England|state=collapsed}}\n\nAt the '''Battle of Edington''', an army of the [[Anglo-Saxon]] kingdom of [[Wessex]] under [[Alfred the Great]] defeated the [[Great Heathen Army]] led by [[Guthrum]] on a date between 6 and 12 May AD&nbsp;878, resulting in the [[Treaty of Wedmore]] later the same year. Primary sources locate the battle at ''\"Ethandun\"'' or ''\"Ethandune\"'', and until a scholarly consensus linked its location with the present-day [[Edington, Wiltshire|Edington]] in [[Wiltshire]] it was known as the '''Battle of ''Ethandun''''', a name which continues to be used.\n\n==Events before the battle==\nThe first Viking raid on Anglo-Saxon England is thought to have been between AD 786 and 802 at [[Isle of Portland|Portland]] in the Kingdom of Wessex, when three Norse ships arrived and killed [[Beorhtric of Wessex|King Beorhtric]]'s [[Reeve (England)|reeve]].<ref name=\"sawyer50\">Sawyer, ''Illustrated History of Vikings'', p. 50</ref> At the other end of the country, in the Kingdom of Northumbria, during AD 793 the holy island of [[Lindisfarne]] was raided.<ref>Anglo-Saxon Chronicle, A.D. 793: \"This year came dreadful fore-warnings over the land of the Northumbrians, terrifying the people most woefully: these were immense sheets of light rushing through the air, and whirlwinds, and fiery dragons flying across the firmament. These tremendous tokens were soon followed by a great famine: and not long after, on the sixth day before the ides of January in the same year, the harrowing inroads of heathen men made lamentable havoc in the church of God in Holy-island (Lindisfarne), by rapine and slaughter.\"</ref> After the sacking of Lindisfarne the raids around the coasts were somewhat sporadic until the 830s when the attacks became more sustained.<ref name=\"sawyer52\">Sawyer, ''Illustrated History of Vikings'', p. 52</ref> In 835, \"heathen men\" ravaged Sheppey.<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/> In 836, [[Egbert of Wessex|Ecgberht of Wessex]] met in battle a force of 35 ships at [[Carhampton]],<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/> and in 838 he faced a combined force of Vikings and [[Cornishman|Cornishmen]] at [[Hingston Down]] in Cornwall.<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/>\n\nThe raiding continued and with each year became more intense.<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/> In 865/866 it escalated further on the arrival of what the Saxons called the [[Great Heathen Army]].<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/> The annals do not report the size of the army, but modern estimates suggest between five hundred and a thousand men.<ref name=jones219 /> It was said to have been under the leadership of the brothers [[Ivar the Boneless]], [[Ubba]], and [[Halfdan Ragnarsson]].<ref name=jones219>Jones, ''A History of the Vikings'', p. 219</ref> What made this army different from those before it was its intent. Its arrival began \"a new stage, that of conquest and residence\".<ref name=jones218 >Jones, ''A History of the Vikings'', p. 218</ref> By 870, the Northmen had conquered the kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Northumbria|Northumbria]] and [[Kingdom of East Anglia|East Anglia]], and in 871 they attacked Wessex. Of the nine battles mentioned by the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' during that year, only one was a West Saxon victory; but in this year Alfred succeeded his brother Ethelred, who died after the [[Battle of Merton]].<ref name=garmonsway70>Garmonsway, ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', pp. 70-73</ref>\n\n[[Mercia]] had collapsed by 874, and the Army's cohesion went with it. Halfdan went back to Northumbria and fought the [[Picts]] and the [[Kingdom of Strathclyde|Strathclyde]] Welsh to secure his northern kingdom.<ref name=\"jones221\">Jones, ''A History of the Vikings'', p. 221</ref> His army settled there and he is not mentioned after 876, when \"[the Danes] were engaged in ploughing and making a living for themselves\".<ref name=\"jones221\"/> Guthrum, with two other unnamed kings, \"departed for [[Cambridge]] in East Anglia\".<ref name=\"jones221\" /> He made several attacks on Wessex, starting in 875, and in the last nearly captured Alfred in his winter fortress at [[Chippenham]].<ref name=\"jones221\" />\nBy 878, the Danes held the east and northeast of England, and their defeat at the [[Battle of Ashdown]] had paused but not halted their advance. Alfred the Great had spent the winter preceding the Battle of Edington in the Somerset marsh of [[Athelney]], the nature of the country giving him some protection. In the spring of 878, he summoned his [[Kingdom of the West Saxons|West Saxon]] forces and marched to Edington, where he met the Danes, led by Guthrum, in battle.\n\n==Alfred's position before the battle==\nGuthrum and his men had applied the usual Danish strategy of occupying a fortified town and waiting for a peace \u201ctreaty,\u201d involving money in return for a promise to leave the kingdom immediately; Alfred shadowed the army, trying to prevent more damage than had already occurred. This started in 875 when Guthrum's army \u201celuded the West Saxon levies and got into Wareham\u201d.<ref name=\"G74\">Garmonsway, ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', p. 74</ref> They then gave hostages and oaths to leave the country to Alfred, who paid them off.<ref name=\"Smyth 70\">Smyth, ''King Alfred the Great'', p. 70</ref> The Danes promptly slipped off to Exeter, even deeper into Alfred's kingdom, where they concluded in the autumn of 877 a \"firm peace\" with Alfred,<ref name=G74/> under terms that entailed their leaving his kingdom and not returning.<ref name=\"Smyth 72\">Smyth, ''King Alfred the Great'', p. 72</ref> This they did, spending the rest of 877 (by the Gregorian calendar) in [[Gloucester]].<ref name=\"Smyth 72\"/> Alfred spent [[Christmas]] at Chippenham, thirty miles from Gloucester. The Danes attacked Chippenham \"in midwinter after Twelfth Night\",<ref name=G74/> probably during the night of 6\u20137 January 878. They captured Chippenham and forced Alfred to retreat \"with a small force\" into the wilderness.<ref name=G74/> It is to this period that the story of King Alfred burning the cakes belongs.<ref name=horspool2>Horspool, ''Why Alfred burnt the cakes'', pp. 2&nbsp;\u2013 3. Although there may have been an early oral tradition about the burning of the cakes, there is no contemporary evidence for the cake story. The first time it appears is one hundred years later and it may have been invented to make an obscure saint [St Neot] look good.</ref>\n\nAlfred seems at this time to have ineffectually chased the Danes around Wessex, while the Danes were in a position to do as they pleased. The ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'' attempts to convey the impression that Alfred held the initiative; it is \"a bland chronicle which laconically charts the movements of the Danish victors while at the same time disingenuously striving to convey the impression that Alfred was in control\",<ref name=\"Smyth 70\" /> although it fails. Even if Alfred had caught up with the Danish force, it is unlikely that he could have accomplished anything. The fact that his army could not defend the fortified Chippenham, even in \"an age... as yet untrained in siege warfare\"<ref name=\"Smyth 70\"/> casts great doubt on its ability to defeat the Danes in an open field, unaided by fortifications. There was little that Alfred could do about the Danish menace between 875 and the end of 877, beyond repeatedly paying the invaders off.\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:King Alfred's Tower, Stourhead, Somerset.jpg|thumb|left| upright=1.4 |[[King Alfred's Tower]] (1772) on one supposed site of ''Egbert's Stone'', the mustering place before the battle.<ref>Horspool, ''Why Alfred Burnt the Cakes'', p. 173. The inscription reads ''ALFRED THE GREAT\nAD 879 on this Summit Erected his Standard Against Danish Invaders To him We owe The Origin of Juries The Establishment of a Militia The Creation of a Naval Force ALFRED The Light of a Benighted Age Was a Philosopher and a Christian The Father of his People The Founder of the English MONARCHY and LIBERTY</ref> ]]\nThis was even truer after the Twelfth Night attack. With his small warband, a fraction of his army at Chippenham, Alfred could not hope to retake the town from the Danes, who had in previous battles (for example at [[Battle of Reading (871)|Reading]] in 871) proved themselves adept at defending fortified positions.<ref name=garmonsway70/> So he retreated to the south, preparing himself and his forces for another battle, and then defeated Guthrum and his host. The first we read of Alfred after the disaster at Chippenham is around [[Easter]], when he built a fortress at [[Athelney]].<ref name=\"g76l26\">Garmonsway. ''The Anglo Saxon Chronicle''. p. 76.</ref><ref name=smyth26>Smyth, ''The Medieval Life of Alfred'', pp. 26\u201327</ref> In the seventh week after Easter, or between 4 and 7 May,<ref name=\"S74\">Smyth, ''King Alfred the Great'', p. 74</ref> Alfred called a [[Conscription#Medieval levies|levy]] at ''Ecgbryhtesstan'' (Egbert's Stone)<ref>Burkitt suggests that on philological grounds, Brixton Deverill may be a contender for the site. Burkitt, Annette, Flesh and Bones of Frome Selwood and Wessex, Hobnob Press 2017, p.335</ref>. Many of the men in the counties around ([[Somerset]], Wiltshire, and [[Hampshire]]) who had not already fled rallied to him there.<ref name=\"g76l26\"/> The next day, Alfred's host moved to Iley Oak<ref> Burkitt suggests that on philological grounds, Iley, written by Asser as 'y glea', may refer to Old Welsh (Asser is writing, a Welshman) 'y lle' 'at the place'. A significant Iron Age hillfort near Edington is called Cley Hill. The English spelling, sounding the same as the old Welsh, may be relevant to understanding the position of the Saxon troops preceding the battle. Burkitt, Annette, Flesh and Bones of Frome Selwood and Wessex, page 328, Hobnob Press 2017</ref>, and then the day after that to ''Ethandun''.<ref name=\"g76l26\"/><ref name=smyth26/><ref>'The Hundred of Warminster', in [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=16071 A History of the County of Wiltshire: Volume 8: Warminster, Westbury and Whorwellsdown Hundreds (1965)], pp. 1-5. Date accessed: 22 May 2010.</ref> There, on an unknown date between 6 and 12 May,<ref>Smyth. ''King Alfred the Great''. p. 75</ref> they fought the Danes. According to the ''Life'':\n\n{{quote|\"Fighting ferociously, forming a dense shield-wall against the whole army of the Pagans, and striving long and bravely...at last he [Alfred] gained the victory. He overthrew the Pagans with great slaughter, and smiting the fugitives, he pursued them as far as the fortress.\"<ref name=smyth26/>}}\n\nAfter the victory, when the Danes had taken refuge in the fortress, the West Saxons removed all food that the Danes might be able to capture in a sortie, and waited.<ref name=smyth26/> After two weeks, the hungry Danes sued for peace, giving Alfred \"preliminary hostages and solemn oaths that they would leave his kingdom immediately\", just as usual, but in addition promising that Guthrum would be baptized.<ref name=\"g76l26\"/> The primary difference between this agreement and the treaties at [[Wareham, Dorset|Wareham]] and [[Exeter]] was that Alfred had decisively defeated the Danes at Edington, rather than just stopping them, and therefore it seemed more likely that they would keep to the terms of the treaty.\n\nThe primary reason for Alfred's victory was probably the relative size of the two armies. The men of even one [[shire]] could be a formidable fighting force, as those of [[Devon]] proved in the same year, defeating an army under [[Ubba|Ubbe Ragnarsson]] at the [[Battle of Cynwit]].<ref name=smyth26/> In addition, in 875 Guthrum had lost the support of other Danish lords, including Ivar and Ubba. Further Danish forces had settled on the land before Guthrum attacked Wessex: in East Anglia, and in Mercia between the treaty at Exeter and the attack on Chippenham; many others were lost in a storm off [[Swanage]] in 876-7, with 120 ships wrecked.<ref name=S74/> Internal disunity was threatening to tear the Danes apart, and they needed time to reorganize. Fortunately for Wessex, they did not use the time available effectively.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Location of the battle==\n[[Image:asser facsimile.png|thumb|right|150px|A 1722 copy of part of Asser's Life of King Alfred.]]\nThe primary sources for the location of the battle are [[Asser]]'s ''Life of King Alfred'', which names the place as \"''Ethandun''\" and the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', which has ''E\u00f0andune''. The chronicle was compiled during the reign of Alfred the Great and is thus a contemporary record.<ref name=asc878>{{cite web|url=http://asc.jebbo.co.uk/a/a-L.html|title=Manuscript A: The Parker Chronicle|website=asc.jebbo.co.uk}}</ref> It is believed that Asser's ''Life'' was originally written in 893; however, no contemporary manuscript survives.<ref name=lapidge84>Keynes/Lapidge, ''Asser's Life of King Alfred'', p. 84 Ch. 56, also a discussion on Asser and the text pp. 48&nbsp;\u2013 58</ref> A version of the Life written in about 1000 AD, known as the ''[[Cotton Otho]] A. xii'' text, lasted until 1731 when it was destroyed in [[Cotton library#Ashburnham House fire|a fire]]. Before its destruction this version had been transcribed and annotated; it is this transcription on which modern translations are based.<ref name=lapidge84/> Some scholars have suggested that Asser's life of King Alfred was a [[Asser#Claims of forgery|forgery]].<ref>See Gransden, ''Historical Writing' Ch. 4 for an analysis of the subject.</ref>\n\nThe location of the battle accepted by most present-day historians is at Edington, near Westbury in Wiltshire.<ref name=lavelle308>Lavelle, ''Alfred's Wars'', pp. 308&nbsp;\u2013 314</ref>  However, the location has been much debated over the centuries.<ref name=lavelle308 /> In 1904 [[W. H. Stevenson|William Henry Stevenson]] analysed possible sites and said \"So far, there is nothing to prove the identity of this ''E\u00f0andune'' [as named in the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle] with Edington\" but then goes on to say that \"there can be little reason for questioning it\".<ref name=stevenson273>Stevenson. [https://archive.org/stream/asserslifekinga00stevgoog#page/n408/mode/2up Asser's life of King Alfred], p. 273. Retrieved 13 February 2013</ref><ref name=whs303 />\n\nThe reasoning to support the ''E\u00f0andune'' of the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle and the ''Ethandun'' of Asser's ''Life'' being Edington in Wiltshire is derived from a trail of information from ancient manuscripts.<ref name=lapidge176>Keynes / Lapidge, ''Alfred the Great'', pp. 176&nbsp;\u2013 177 and fn. 90 p. 323</ref><ref>Stevenson. [https://archive.org/stream/asserslifekinga00stevgoog#page/n180/mode/2up Asser's Life of King Alfred: Asserius De Rebus Gestis \u00c6lfredi], p. 45 Ch. 56. Retrieved 13 February 2013</ref> Edington, Wiltshire, is known to have been part of Alfred's family estate.<ref name=lapidge176/> He left a manor called ''E\u00f0andune'' to his wife in his will.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esawyer.org.uk/charter/1507.html|title=Electronic Sawyer|website=www.esawyer.org.uk}}</ref> A charter records a meeting of the king's council at ''E\u00f0andun'', although a later scribe has annotated the same document with ''E\u00f0andune''.<ref name=whs303>[https://archive.org/stream/p2athenaeum1906lond#page/302/mode/2up Stevenson. The battle of Ethandun] ''in'' ''The Athenaeum'', Number 4116. pp. 303-304. Retrieved 29 January 2014</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esawyer.org.uk/charter/646.html|title=Electronic Sawyer|website=www.esawyer.org.uk}}</ref> In 968, another charter reported that King Edgar had granted land at ''Edyndon'' to Romsey Abbey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esawyer.org.uk/charter/765.html|title=Electronic Sawyer|website=www.esawyer.org.uk}}</ref> The [[Domesday book]] has an entry for Romsey Abbey holding land at ''Edendone'' (''Wilt'schire'') at the time of [[Edward the Confessor]] and also in 1086, and this is known to be at Edington, Wiltshire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://domesdaymap.co.uk/place/ST9253/edington/|title=Edington - Domesday Book|website=domesdaymap.co.uk|access-date=4 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201193043/http://domesdaymap.co.uk/place/ST9253/edington/|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Edendonedb.png|thumb|right|Extract from ''Domesday Book'' showing Edington as Edendone]]\n\nAlternatives to Edington, Wiltshire, have been suggested since early times. The [[Tudor dynasty|Tudor]] historian [[Polydore Vergil]] appears to have misread the ancient texts for the battle site, as he places it at ''Abyndoniam'' (Abingdon) instead of Edington.<ref>Polydore Vergil, ''Anglica Historia'' (1555 edition) Book V, [http://www.philological.bham.ac.uk/polverg/5lat.html#7 Ch. 7 online]</ref><ref>Lavelle, Alfred's Wars. pp. 306&nbsp;\u2013 307</ref> In the 19th century there was a resurgence in interest of medieval history and King Alfred was seen as a major hero.<ref name=parker3>Parker, ''England's Darling'', Ch. 3</ref> Although most early historians had sited the battle as in the Edington, Wiltshire area, the significant interest in the subject encouraged many antiquarians to dig up Alfredian sites and also to propose alternatives for the location of the battle.<ref>Lavelle, ''Alfred's Wars'', p. 309</ref><ref name=parker18>Parker, ''England's Darling'', pp. 18&nbsp;\u2013 22</ref> Arguments for the alternative sites were generally name-based, although with the large interest in everything Alfredian in the 19th century, any site that had an Alfred connection could be guaranteed large numbers of tourists, so this was also a driving force to find a link.<ref name=parker18/><ref name=lavelle311>Lavelle, ''Alfred's Wars'', pp. 311&nbsp;\u2013 312</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Some alternative suggestions for the battle site, by author\n|- align=center\n! Author\n! Year\n! Location of ''Ethandun''\n|-\n| [[Daniel Lysons (antiquarian)|Daniel Lysons]] || 1806 || Eddington, Berkshire<ref>Lysons. [https://books.google.com/books?id=W3kgAQAAMAAJ&dq=Magna%20Britannia%3B%3A%20being%20a%20concise%20topographical%20account%20eddington&pg=PA163#v=onepage&q=eddington Magna Britannia. ] Vol 1. p. 162. Googlebooks Retrieved 4 March 2012</ref>\n|-\n| J. Whitaker || 1809 || Slaughterford, Wiltshire<ref>Whitaker. [https://books.google.com/books?id=EycwAAAAYAAJ&q=ethandun#v=snippet The Life of St Neot.] pp. 268&nbsp;\u2013 269. Googlebooks Retrieved 5 March 2012</ref>\n|-\n| J. M. Moffat || 1834 || 'Woeful Danes', Michinhampton, Gloucestershire<ref>J.M.Moffat. [https://books.google.com/books?id=aY8MAAAAYAAJ&vq=106&pg=PA106#v=onepage&q=ethandun Battle of Ethandun] pp. 106&nbsp;\u2013 110 ''in'' Brayley. The graphic and Historical Illustrator. Googlebooks Retrieved 4 March 2012</ref>\n|-\n| J. Thurnham || 1857 || West Yatton, Wiltshire<ref>Thurnham, [https://archive.org/stream/wiltshirearchaeo03wilt#page/66/mode/2up On the barrow at Lanhill near Chippenham, with remarks on the site of and the events connected with the battles of Cynuit and Ethandun.] pp. 67&nbsp;\u2013 86 ''in'' Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine: 3</ref>\n|- \n| [[George Julius Poulett Scrope|G. Poulett Scrope]] || 1858 || Etton-Down, Yatton, Wiltshire<ref>G. Poulett-Scrope.[https://archive.org/stream/wiltshirearchaeo04wilt#page/298/mode/2upThe Battle of Ethandun.] pp. 298&nbsp;\u2013 308 ''in'' Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine: 4</ref>\n|- \n| W. H. P. Greswell || 1910 || Edington, Somerset<ref>Greswell. [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924027953276#page/n71/mode/2up Battle of Edington.] p. 52. Retrieved 19 December 2012</ref>\n|- \n| Albany Major || 1913 || Edington, Somerset<ref>{{cite book|last1=Major|first1=Albany|title=Early wars of Wessex|date=1913|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|url=https://archive.org/stream/earlywarsofwesse00majorich#page/156/mode/2up|pages=157\u2013167}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Consequences==\n[[File:England 878.svg|thumb|300px|{{center|England, 878}}]]\nThree weeks after the battle, Guthrum was baptized at [[Aller, Somerset|Aller]] in [[Somerset]] with Alfred as his sponsor.<ref name=asc878 /><ref name=asser85>Asser, ''Life'', ch. 56</ref> It is possible that the enforced conversion was an attempt by Alfred to lock Guthrum into a Christian code of ethics, hoping it would ensure the Danes' compliance with any treaties agreed to. The converted Guthrum took the baptismal name of Athelstan.<ref name=yorke176>Yorke, ''Kings and Kingdoms'', p. 176&nbsp;\u2013 177</ref>\n\nUnder the terms of the [[Treaty of Wedmore]], the converted Guthrum was required to leave Wessex and return to East Anglia. Consequently, in 879 the Viking army left Chippenham and made its way to Cirencester and remained there for a year.<ref name=asser57>Asser, ''Life'', ch. 57</ref> The following year the army went to East Anglia, where it settled.<ref name=asser60>Asser. Life. ch. 60</ref>\n\nAlso in 879, according to Asser, another Viking army sailed up the River Thames and wintered at Fulham.<ref name=asser58>Asser, ''Life'', ch. 58</ref> Over the next few years this particular Danish faction had several encounters with Alfred's forces. However, Alfred managed to contain this threat by reforming his military and setting up a system of fortified cities, known as ''burghs'' or [[burh]]s.<ref name=yorke176 />\n\nIn 885 Asser reports that the Viking army that had settled in East Anglia had broken ''in a most insolent manner'' the peace they had established with Alfred, although Guthrum is not mentioned.<ref name=asser72>Asser, ''Life'', ch. 72</ref> Guthrum reigned as king in East Anglia until his death in 890, and although this period was not always peaceful he was not considered a threat.<ref name=yorke176 /><ref name=asc890>ASC 890. English translation at [http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/657/pg657.html Project Gutenberg]</ref>\n\nIn 886, the Treaty of Alfred and Guthrum defined the boundaries of their two kingdoms. The kingdom of Mercia was divided up, with part going to Alfred's Wessex and the other part to Guthrum's East Anglia.<ref name=att96>[https://archive.org/stream/lawsofearliesten00grea#page/96/mode/2up The treaty of Alfred and Guthrum] in Attenborough's ''The laws of the earliest English kings'', pp. 96-101. Retrieved 28 January 2014</ref> The agreement also defined the social classes of Danish East Anglia and their equivalents in Wessex. It tried to provide a framework that would minimize conflict and regulate commerce between the two peoples.<ref name=abels165>Abels, ''Alfred the Great: War, Kingship and Culture in Anglo-Saxon England'', pp. 165-67</ref> It is not clear how seriously Guthrum took his conversion to Christianity, but he was the first of the Danish rulers of the English kingdoms to mint coins on the Alfredian model, under his baptismal name of Athelstan. By the end of the 9th century, all of the Anglo-Danish rulers were minting coins too. By the 10th century, the Anglo-Saxon model of kingship seems to have been universally adopted by the Anglo-Danish leadership.<ref name=abels165 />\n\nAfter the defeat of Guthrum at the Battle of Edington, Alfred's reforms to military obligations in Wessex made it increasingly difficult for the Vikings to raid successfully. By 896 the Vikings gave up with some going to East Anglia and others going to Northumbria. It was under Alfred that the Viking threat was contained. However, the system of military reforms and the [[Burghal Hidage]] introduced by [[Edward the Elder]] enabled Alfred's successors to retake control of the lands occupied in the [[Danelaw|North of England]] by the Danes.<ref name=horspool>Horspool, ''Why Alfred Burnt the Cakes'', pp. 104-110</ref><ref name=asc896>ASC 896, ASC 897. English translation at [http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/657/pg657.html Project Gutenberg]</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==The battle in fiction==\nThe battle features in several historical novels and dramas:\n* ''The Marsh King'', by [[C. Walter Hodges]]\n* ''The Raven and the Cross'', a children's television serial\n* ''[[The Ballad of the White Horse]]'', by [[G. K. Chesterton]] (who also wrote about the battle in ''Ethandune'', collected in ''Alarms and Discursions'')\n* ''[[The Last Kingdom]]'', by [[Bernard Cornwell]] pages 166-169\n* ''[[The Last Kingdom (TV series)|The Last Kingdom]]'', Season 1, Episode 8 in the television series based on Bernard Cornwell's novels\n* ''[[Sarum (novel)|Sarum]]'' by [[Edward Rutherfurd]]\n* ''[[Flesh and Bones of Frome Selwood and Wessex]]'', by [[Annette Burkitt]], pages 361-379, Hobnob Press 2017\n\n==See also==\n* Viking [[Siege of Paris (885\u201386)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://asc.jebbo.co.uk/a/a-L.html|title=The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle: An Electronic Edition (Vol 1) literary edition|\npublisher=Tony Jebson|accessdate=4 March 2012}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://domesdaymap.co.uk/|title=Domesday Map Online|publisher=Hull University|accessdate=4 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321162208/http://domesdaymap.co.uk/|archive-date=21 March 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Abels|first=Richard P|title=Alfred the Great: War, Kingship and Culture in Anglo-Saxon England|publisher=Routledge|location=Abingdon, Oxon|year=1998|isbn=0-582-04048-5}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Asser |authorlink=Asser |contribution=Life of King Alfred|editor-first=Simon|editor-last=Keynes |editor2-first=Michael |editor2-last=Lapidge |title=Alfred the Great: Asser's Life of King Alfred & Other Contemporary Sources |publisher=Penguin Classics |year=1983|isbn=978-0-14-044409-4}}\n*{{Cite book|editor-last=Attenborough|editor-first=F.L. Tr|title=The laws of the earliest English kings|publisher=Cambridge University Press\n|location=Cambridge|year=1922}}\n* {{Cite book|editor-last=Brayley|editor-first=Edward Wedlake|title=The graphic and Historical Illustrator|year=1834|publisher=J.Chidle|location=London}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=16071|publisher= British History Online|title=A History of the County of Wiltshire: Volume 8: Warminster, Westbury and Whorwellsdown Hundreds|author=Crittall, Elizabeth|accessdate=22 May 2010}}\n* {{Cite book|editor-last=Garmonsway|editor-first= G. N.| title=The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle|location=London|publisher= Dent|year =1972|isbn=0-460-11624-X }}\n* {{Cite book|last=Gransden|first=Antonia|title=Historical Writing in England: c. 500 to c. 1307|isbn=0-415-15124-4 |publisher=Routledge|year=1996|location=London}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Greswell|first=William H. P.|title=The story of the Battle of Edington|publisher=The Wessex Press|location=Taunton|year=1910}}\n* {{Cite book|authorlink=David Horspool|last=Horspool|first= David|title=Why Alfred Burned the Cakes|location=London|publisher= Profile Books|year= 2006|isbn=978-1-86197-779-3}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Jones|first= Gwyn|title=A History of the Vikings|location= Oxford|publisher= Oxford University Press|year=1984|isbn=0-19-215882-1 }}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.esawyer.org.uk|title=The Electronic Sawyer an online version of the revised edition of Sawyer's Anglo-Saxon Charters section one [S 1-1602]|publisher=Kings College|location = London|last1=Kelly|first1=S.E|last2=Miller|first2=Sean|accessdate=19 December 2012}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Lavelle|first=Ryan|title=Alfred's Wars Sources and Interpretations of Anglo-Saxon Warfare in the Viking Age|publisher=Boydel Press|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-84383-569-1|year=2010}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Lysons|first1=Daniel|last2=Lysons|first2=Samuel|title=Magna Britannia being a concise topographical account of the several counties of Great Britain. Vol. 1. Bedfordshire, Berkshire, Buckinghamshire|location=London|year=1806|publisher=T.Cadell and W.Davies}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.trin.cam.ac.uk/chartwww/New%20RegestaIntro.html|title=The New Regesta Regum Anglorum|editor=Miller, Sean|publisher=British Academy - Royal Historical Society|accessdate=4 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927003641/http://www.trin.cam.ac.uk/chartwww/New%20RegestaIntro.html|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Parker|first=Joanne|title='England's Darling'|publisher=Manchester University Press|location=Manchester|year=2007|isbn=978-0-7190-7356-4}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=The Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine: 3|year=1857|publisher=Wiltshire Archaeological Society|location=Devizes, Wiltshire}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=The Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine: 4|year=1858|publisher=Wiltshire Archaeological Society|location=Devizes, Wiltshire}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.ukniwm.org.uk/server/show/conMemorial.45340/fromUkniwmSearch/1|publisher= United Kingdom National Inventory of War Memorials|title=Battle of Ethandun|accessdate=21 May 2010}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Sawyer|first= Peter|title=The Oxford Illustrated History of the Vikings. 3rd Edition|location=Oxford|publisher= OUP|year= 2001|isbn=0-19-285434-8}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Smyth|first=Alfred P.|title=King Alfred the Great|location= Oxford|publisher= Oxford University Press|year=1995|isbn=0-19-822989-5}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Smyth|first= Alfred P. |title=The Medieval Life of King Alfred the Great: A Translation and Commentary on the Text Attributed to Asser|year=2002|publisher= Paulgrave Houndmills|location=Basingstoke, Hampshire|isbn=0-333-69917-3}}\n* {{Cite book|editor-last=Stevenson|editor-first=William Henry|title=Asser's Life of King Alfred together with the annals of Saint Neots erroneously ascribed to Asser|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1904|location=Oxford}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Stevenson|first=W H|journal=The Athenaeum Journal|volume=4116|title=The Battle of Ethandun|publisher=J.C.Francis and J.E.Francis|location=London|date=15 September 1906|pages=303\u2013304}}\n* {{Cite web|last=Vergil|first=Polydore|authorlink=Polydore Vergil|editor-first=Dana F|editor-last= Sutton|title=Angelica Historia (Online Ed.)|year=1555|publisher=Hosted by University of Birmingham|url=http://www.philological.bham.ac.uk/polverg/|accessdate=5 March 2012}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Whitaker|first=John|title=The Life of Saint Neot the oldest of all brothers to King Alfred|publisher=John Joseph Stockwell|year=1809|location=London}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Yorke|first=Barbara|authorlink=Barbara Yorke|title=Kings and Kingdoms of Anglo-Saxon England|publisher=Routledge|location=London|year=1997|isbn=0-415-16639-X}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p003k9gm BBC Radio 4 Archive Programme - In Our Time: ''Alfred and the Battle of Edington'']\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Viking Invasion of England}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethandun}}\n[[Category:870s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Wessex]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Vikings]]\n[[Category:Military history of Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Anglo-Saxons]]\n[[Category:878]]\n[[Category:9th century in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{bots|deny=InternetArchiveBot}}\n{{coord |51|15|50|N|02|08|34|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Edington\n|partof=the [[Norse activity in the British Isles|Viking invasions of England]]\n|date=May 878\n|image=Ethandunmem.jpg\n|image_size=200px\n|caption=Memorial to the ''Battle of Ethandun'' erected in 2000 near the [[hillfort]] of [[Bratton Castle]].<ref>UK Inventory of War Memorials. The Memorial stone plaque reads:{{quote|''TO COMMEMORATE THE BATTLE OF ETHANDUN FOUGHT IN THIS VICINITY MAY 878 AD WHEN KING ALFRED THE GREAT DEFEATED THE VIKING ARMY, GIVING BIRTH TO THE ENGLISH NATIONHOOD. UNVEILED BY THE 7TH MARQUESS OF BATH 5TH NOVEMBER 2000.''}}\nAn additional inscription reads:\n{{quote| ''THIS STONE, PRESENTED BY F. SWANTON AND SONS, NORTH FARM, WEST OVERTON, IS A SARSEN STONE SIMILAR TO THOSE AT KINGSTON DEVERILL, THE AREA WHERE KING ALFRED RALLIED SAXON LEVIES FROM HAMPSHIRE, WILTSHIRE AND SOMERSET TO MARCH AGAINST GUTHRUM'S VIKING ARMY BASED AT CHIPPENHAM.''}}</ref>\n|place= Probably [[Edington, Wiltshire|Edington]], Wiltshire\n|casus=\n|territory=\n|result=Decisive West Saxon victory\n|combatant1= [[Wessex|West Saxons]]\n|combatant2= [[Danelaw]] [[Vikings]]\n|commander1=[[Alfred the Great]]\n|commander2=[[Guthrum the Old]]\n|strength1=unknown\n|strength2=unknown\n|casualties1=unknown\n|casualties2=unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Viking invasions of England|state=collapsed}}\n\nAt the '''Battle of Edington''', an army of the [[Anglo-Saxon]] kingdom of [[Wessex]] under [[Alfred the Great]] defeated the [[Great Heathen Army]] led by [[Guthrum]] on a date between 6 and 12 May AD&nbsp;878, resulting in the [[Treaty of Wedmore]] later the same year. Primary sources locate the battle at ''\"Ethandun\"'' or ''\"Ethandune\"'', and until a scholarly consensus linked its location with the present-day [[Edington, Wiltshire|Edington]] in [[Wiltshire]] it was known as the '''Battle of ''Ethandun''''', a name which continues to be used.\n\n==Events before the battle==\nThe first Viking raid on Anglo-Saxon England is thought to have been between AD 786 and 802 at [[Isle of Portland|Portland]] in the Kingdom of Wessex, when three Norse ships arrived and killed [[Beorhtric of Wessex|King Beorhtric]]'s [[Reeve (England)|reeve]].<ref name=\"sawyer50\">Sawyer, ''Illustrated History of Vikings'', p. 50</ref> At the other end of the country, in the Kingdom of Northumbria, during AD 793 the holy island of [[Lindisfarne]] was raided.<ref>Anglo-Saxon Chronicle, A.D. 793: \"This year came dreadful fore-warnings over the land of the Northumbrians, terrifying the people most woefully: these were immense sheets of light rushing through the air, and whirlwinds, and fiery dragons flying across the firmament. These tremendous tokens were soon followed by a great famine: and not long after, on the sixth day before the ides of January in the same year, the harrowing inroads of heathen men made lamentable havoc in the church of God in Holy-island (Lindisfarne), by rapine and slaughter.\"</ref> After the sacking of Lindisfarne the raids around the coasts were somewhat sporadic until the 830s when the attacks became more sustained.<ref name=\"sawyer52\">Sawyer, ''Illustrated History of Vikings'', p. 52</ref> In 835, \"heathen men\" ravaged Sheppey.<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/> In 836, [[Egbert of Wessex|Ecgberht of Wessex]] met in battle a force of 35 ships at [[Carhampton]],<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/> and in 838 he faced a combined force of Vikings and [[Cornishman|Cornishmen]] at [[Hingston Down]] in Cornwall.<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/>\n\nThe raiding continued and with each year became more intense.<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/> In 865/866 it escalated further on the arrival of what the Saxons called the [[Great Heathen Army]].<ref name=\"sawyer52\"/> The annals do not report the size of the army, but modern estimates suggest between five hundred and a thousand men.<ref name=jones219 /> It was said to have been under the leadership of the brothers [[Ivar the Boneless]], [[Ubba]], and [[Halfdan Ragnarsson]].<ref name=jones219>Jones, ''A History of the Vikings'', p. 219</ref> What made this army different from those before it was its intent. Its arrival began \"a new stage, that of conquest and residence\".<ref name=jones218 >Jones, ''A History of the Vikings'', p. 218</ref> By 870, the Northmen had conquered the kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Northumbria|Northumbria]] and [[Kingdom of East Anglia|East Anglia]], and in 871 they attacked Wessex. Of the nine battles mentioned by the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' during that year, only one was a West Saxon victory; but in this year Alfred succeeded his brother Ethelred, who died after the [[Battle of Merton]].<ref name=garmonsway70>Garmonsway, ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', pp. 70-73</ref>\n\n[[Mercia]] had collapsed by 874, and the Army's cohesion went with it. Halfdan went back to Northumbria and fought the [[Picts]] and the [[Kingdom of Strathclyde|Strathclyde]] Welsh to secure his northern kingdom.<ref name=\"jones221\">Jones, ''A History of the Vikings'', p. 221</ref> His army settled there and he is not mentioned after 876, when \"[the Danes] were engaged in ploughing and making a living for themselves\".<ref name=\"jones221\"/> Guthrum, with two other unnamed kings, \"departed for [[Cambridge]] in East Anglia\".<ref name=\"jones221\" /> He made several attacks on Wessex, starting in 875, and in the last nearly captured Alfred in his winter fortress at [[Chippenham]].<ref name=\"jones221\" />\nBy 878, the Danes held the east and northeast of England, and their defeat at the [[Battle of Ashdown]] had paused but not halted their advance. Alfred the Great had spent the winter preceding the Battle of Edington in the Somerset marsh of [[Athelney]], the nature of the country giving him some protection. In the spring of 878, he summoned his [[Kingdom of the West Saxons|West Saxon]] forces and marched to Edington, where he met the Danes, led by Guthrum, in battle.\n\n==Alfred's position before the battle==\nGuthrum and his men had applied the usual Danish strategy of occupying a fortified town and waiting for a peace \u201ctreaty,\u201d involving money in return for a promise to leave the kingdom immediately; Alfred shadowed the army, trying to prevent more damage than had already occurred. This started in 875 when Guthrum's army \u201celuded the West Saxon levies and got into Wareham\u201d.<ref name=\"G74\">Garmonsway, ''The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', p. 74</ref> They then gave hostages and oaths to leave the country to Alfred, who paid them off.<ref name=\"Smyth 70\">Smyth, ''King Alfred the Great'', p. 70</ref> The Danes promptly slipped off to Exeter, even deeper into Alfred's kingdom, where they concluded in the autumn of 877 a \"firm peace\" with Alfred,<ref name=G74/> under terms that entailed their leaving his kingdom and not returning.<ref name=\"Smyth 72\">Smyth, ''King Alfred the Great'', p. 72</ref> This they did, spending the rest of 877 (by the Gregorian calendar) in [[Gloucester]].<ref name=\"Smyth 72\"/> Alfred spent [[Christmas]] at Chippenham, thirty miles from Gloucester. The Danes attacked Chippenham \"in midwinter after Twelfth Night\",<ref name=G74/> probably during the night of 6\u20137 January 878. They captured Chippenham and forced Alfred to retreat \"with a small force\" into the wilderness.<ref name=G74/> It is to this period that the story of King Alfred burning the cakes belongs.<ref name=horspool2>Horspool, ''Why Alfred burnt the cakes'', pp. 2&nbsp;\u2013 3. Although there may have been an early oral tradition about the burning of the cakes, there is no contemporary evidence for the cake story. The first time it appears is one hundred years later and it may have been invented to make an obscure saint [St Neot] look good.</ref>\n\nAlfred seems at this time to have ineffectually chased the Danes around Wessex, while the Danes were in a position to do as they pleased. The ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'' attempts to convey the impression that Alfred held the initiative; it is \"a bland chronicle which laconically charts the movements of the Danish victors while at the same time disingenuously striving to convey the impression that Alfred was in control\",<ref name=\"Smyth 70\" /> although it fails. Even if Alfred had caught up with the Danish force, it is unlikely that he could have accomplished anything. The fact that his army could not defend the fortified Chippenham, even in \"an age... as yet untrained in siege warfare\"<ref name=\"Smyth 70\"/> casts great doubt on its ability to defeat the Danes in an open field, unaided by fortifications. There was little that Alfred could do about the Danish menace between 875 and the end of 877, beyond repeatedly paying the invaders off.\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:King Alfred's Tower, Stourhead, Somerset.jpg|thumb|left| upright=1.4 |[[King Alfred's Tower]] (1772) on one supposed site of ''Egbert's Stone'', the mustering place before the battle.<ref>Horspool, ''Why Alfred Burnt the Cakes'', p. 173. The inscription reads ''ALFRED THE GREAT\nAD 879 on this Summit Erected his Standard Against Danish Invaders To him We owe The Origin of Juries The Establishment of a Militia The Creation of a Naval Force ALFRED The Light of a Benighted Age Was a Philosopher and a Christian The Father of his People The Founder of the English MONARCHY and LIBERTY</ref> ]]\nThis was even truer after the Twelfth Night attack. With his small warband, a fraction of his army at Chippenham, Alfred could not hope to retake the town from the Danes, who had in previous battles (for example at [[Battle of Reading (871)|Reading]] in 871) proved themselves adept at defending fortified positions.<ref name=garmonsway70/> So he retreated to the south, preparing himself and his forces for another battle, and then defeated Guthrum and his host. The first we read of Alfred after the disaster at Chippenham is around [[Easter]], when he built a fortress at [[Athelney]].<ref name=\"g76l26\">Garmonsway. ''The Anglo Saxon Chronicle''. p. 76.</ref><ref name=smyth26>Smyth, ''The Medieval Life of Alfred'', pp. 26\u201327</ref> In the seventh week after Easter, or between 4 and 7 May,<ref name=\"S74\">Smyth, ''King Alfred the Great'', p. 74</ref> Alfred called a [[Conscription#Medieval levies|levy]] at ''Ecgbryhtesstan'' (Egbert's Stone)<ref>Burkitt suggests that philologically, Brixton Deverill may be a contender for the site. Burkitt, Annette, Flesh and Bones of Frome Selwood and Wessex, Hobnob Press 2017, p.335</ref>. Many of the men in the counties around ([[Somerset]], Wiltshire, and [[Hampshire]]) who had not already fled rallied to him there.<ref name=\"g76l26\"/> The next day, Alfred's host moved to Iley Oak, and then the day after that to ''Ethandun''.<ref name=\"g76l26\"/><ref name=smyth26/><ref>'The Hundred of Warminster', in [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=16071 A History of the County of Wiltshire: Volume 8: Warminster, Westbury and Whorwellsdown Hundreds (1965)], pp. 1-5. Date accessed: 22 May 2010.</ref> There, on an unknown date between 6 and 12 May,<ref>Smyth. ''King Alfred the Great''. p. 75</ref> they fought the Danes. According to the ''Life'':\n\n{{quote|\"Fighting ferociously, forming a dense shield-wall against the whole army of the Pagans, and striving long and bravely...at last he [Alfred] gained the victory. He overthrew the Pagans with great slaughter, and smiting the fugitives, he pursued them as far as the fortress.\"<ref name=smyth26/>}}\n\nAfter the victory, when the Danes had taken refuge in the fortress, the West Saxons removed all food that the Danes might be able to capture in a sortie, and waited.<ref name=smyth26/> After two weeks, the hungry Danes sued for peace, giving Alfred \"preliminary hostages and solemn oaths that they would leave his kingdom immediately\", just as usual, but in addition promising that Guthrum would be baptized.<ref name=\"g76l26\"/> The primary difference between this agreement and the treaties at [[Wareham, Dorset|Wareham]] and [[Exeter]] was that Alfred had decisively defeated the Danes at Edington, rather than just stopping them, and therefore it seemed more likely that they would keep to the terms of the treaty.\n\nThe primary reason for Alfred's victory was probably the relative size of the two armies. The men of even one [[shire]] could be a formidable fighting force, as those of [[Devon]] proved in the same year, defeating an army under [[Ubba|Ubbe Ragnarsson]] at the [[Battle of Cynwit]].<ref name=smyth26/> In addition, in 875 Guthrum had lost the support of other Danish lords, including Ivar and Ubba. Further Danish forces had settled on the land before Guthrum attacked Wessex: in East Anglia, and in Mercia between the treaty at Exeter and the attack on Chippenham; many others were lost in a storm off [[Swanage]] in 876-7, with 120 ships wrecked.<ref name=S74/> Internal disunity was threatening to tear the Danes apart, and they needed time to reorganize. Fortunately for Wessex, they did not use the time available effectively.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Location of the battle==\n[[Image:asser facsimile.png|thumb|right|150px|A 1722 copy of part of Asser's Life of King Alfred.]]\nThe primary sources for the location of the battle are [[Asser]]'s ''Life of King Alfred'', which names the place as \"''Ethandun''\" and the ''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'', which has ''E\u00f0andune''. The chronicle was compiled during the reign of Alfred the Great and is thus a contemporary record.<ref name=asc878>{{cite web|url=http://asc.jebbo.co.uk/a/a-L.html|title=Manuscript A: The Parker Chronicle|website=asc.jebbo.co.uk}}</ref> It is believed that Asser's ''Life'' was originally written in 893; however, no contemporary manuscript survives.<ref name=lapidge84>Keynes/Lapidge, ''Asser's Life of King Alfred'', p. 84 Ch. 56, also a discussion on Asser and the text pp. 48&nbsp;\u2013 58</ref> A version of the Life written in about 1000 AD, known as the ''[[Cotton Otho]] A. xii'' text, lasted until 1731 when it was destroyed in [[Cotton library#Ashburnham House fire|a fire]]. Before its destruction this version had been transcribed and annotated; it is this transcription on which modern translations are based.<ref name=lapidge84/> Some scholars have suggested that Asser's life of King Alfred was a [[Asser#Claims of forgery|forgery]].<ref>See Gransden, ''Historical Writing' Ch. 4 for an analysis of the subject.</ref>\n\nThe location of the battle accepted by most present-day historians is at Edington, near Westbury in Wiltshire.<ref name=lavelle308>Lavelle, ''Alfred's Wars'', pp. 308&nbsp;\u2013 314</ref>  However, the location has been much debated over the centuries.<ref name=lavelle308 /> In 1904 [[W. H. Stevenson|William Henry Stevenson]] analysed possible sites and said \"So far, there is nothing to prove the identity of this ''E\u00f0andune'' [as named in the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle] with Edington\" but then goes on to say that \"there can be little reason for questioning it\".<ref name=stevenson273>Stevenson. [https://archive.org/stream/asserslifekinga00stevgoog#page/n408/mode/2up Asser's life of King Alfred], p. 273. Retrieved 13 February 2013</ref><ref name=whs303 />\n\nThe reasoning to support the ''E\u00f0andune'' of the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle and the ''Ethandun'' of Asser's ''Life'' being Edington in Wiltshire is derived from a trail of information from ancient manuscripts.<ref name=lapidge176>Keynes / Lapidge, ''Alfred the Great'', pp. 176&nbsp;\u2013 177 and fn. 90 p. 323</ref><ref>Stevenson. [https://archive.org/stream/asserslifekinga00stevgoog#page/n180/mode/2up Asser's Life of King Alfred: Asserius De Rebus Gestis \u00c6lfredi], p. 45 Ch. 56. Retrieved 13 February 2013</ref> Edington, Wiltshire, is known to have been part of Alfred's family estate.<ref name=lapidge176/> He left a manor called ''E\u00f0andune'' to his wife in his will.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esawyer.org.uk/charter/1507.html|title=Electronic Sawyer|website=www.esawyer.org.uk}}</ref> A charter records a meeting of the king's council at ''E\u00f0andun'', although a later scribe has annotated the same document with ''E\u00f0andune''.<ref name=whs303>[https://archive.org/stream/p2athenaeum1906lond#page/302/mode/2up Stevenson. The battle of Ethandun] ''in'' ''The Athenaeum'', Number 4116. pp. 303-304. Retrieved 29 January 2014</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esawyer.org.uk/charter/646.html|title=Electronic Sawyer|website=www.esawyer.org.uk}}</ref> In 968, another charter reported that King Edgar had granted land at ''Edyndon'' to Romsey Abbey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esawyer.org.uk/charter/765.html|title=Electronic Sawyer|website=www.esawyer.org.uk}}</ref> The [[Domesday book]] has an entry for Romsey Abbey holding land at ''Edendone'' (''Wilt'schire'') at the time of [[Edward the Confessor]] and also in 1086, and this is known to be at Edington, Wiltshire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://domesdaymap.co.uk/place/ST9253/edington/|title=Edington - Domesday Book|website=domesdaymap.co.uk|access-date=4 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201193043/http://domesdaymap.co.uk/place/ST9253/edington/|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Edendonedb.png|thumb|right|Extract from ''Domesday Book'' showing Edington as Edendone]]\n\nAlternatives to Edington, Wiltshire, have been suggested since early times. The [[Tudor dynasty|Tudor]] historian [[Polydore Vergil]] appears to have misread the ancient texts for the battle site, as he places it at ''Abyndoniam'' (Abingdon) instead of Edington.<ref>Polydore Vergil, ''Anglica Historia'' (1555 edition) Book V, [http://www.philological.bham.ac.uk/polverg/5lat.html#7 Ch. 7 online]</ref><ref>Lavelle, Alfred's Wars. pp. 306&nbsp;\u2013 307</ref> In the 19th century there was a resurgence in interest of medieval history and King Alfred was seen as a major hero.<ref name=parker3>Parker, ''England's Darling'', Ch. 3</ref> Although most early historians had sited the battle as in the Edington, Wiltshire area, the significant interest in the subject encouraged many antiquarians to dig up Alfredian sites and also to propose alternatives for the location of the battle.<ref>Lavelle, ''Alfred's Wars'', p. 309</ref><ref name=parker18>Parker, ''England's Darling'', pp. 18&nbsp;\u2013 22</ref> Arguments for the alternative sites were generally name-based, although with the large interest in everything Alfredian in the 19th century, any site that had an Alfred connection could be guaranteed large numbers of tourists, so this was also a driving force to find a link.<ref name=parker18/><ref name=lavelle311>Lavelle, ''Alfred's Wars'', pp. 311&nbsp;\u2013 312</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Some alternative suggestions for the battle site, by author\n|- align=center\n! Author\n! Year\n! Location of ''Ethandun''\n|-\n| [[Daniel Lysons (antiquarian)|Daniel Lysons]] || 1806 || Eddington, Berkshire<ref>Lysons. [https://books.google.com/books?id=W3kgAQAAMAAJ&dq=Magna%20Britannia%3B%3A%20being%20a%20concise%20topographical%20account%20eddington&pg=PA163#v=onepage&q=eddington Magna Britannia. ] Vol 1. p. 162. Googlebooks Retrieved 4 March 2012</ref>\n|-\n| J. Whitaker || 1809 || Slaughterford, Wiltshire<ref>Whitaker. [https://books.google.com/books?id=EycwAAAAYAAJ&q=ethandun#v=snippet The Life of St Neot.] pp. 268&nbsp;\u2013 269. Googlebooks Retrieved 5 March 2012</ref>\n|-\n| J. M. Moffat || 1834 || 'Woeful Danes', Michinhampton, Gloucestershire<ref>J.M.Moffat. [https://books.google.com/books?id=aY8MAAAAYAAJ&vq=106&pg=PA106#v=onepage&q=ethandun Battle of Ethandun] pp. 106&nbsp;\u2013 110 ''in'' Brayley. The graphic and Historical Illustrator. Googlebooks Retrieved 4 March 2012</ref>\n|-\n| J. Thurnham || 1857 || West Yatton, Wiltshire<ref>Thurnham, [https://archive.org/stream/wiltshirearchaeo03wilt#page/66/mode/2up On the barrow at Lanhill near Chippenham, with remarks on the site of and the events connected with the battles of Cynuit and Ethandun.] pp. 67&nbsp;\u2013 86 ''in'' Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine: 3</ref>\n|- \n| [[George Julius Poulett Scrope|G. Poulett Scrope]] || 1858 || Etton-Down, Yatton, Wiltshire<ref>G. Poulett-Scrope.[https://archive.org/stream/wiltshirearchaeo04wilt#page/298/mode/2upThe Battle of Ethandun.] pp. 298&nbsp;\u2013 308 ''in'' Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine: 4</ref>\n|- \n| W. H. P. Greswell || 1910 || Edington, Somerset<ref>Greswell. [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924027953276#page/n71/mode/2up Battle of Edington.] p. 52. Retrieved 19 December 2012</ref>\n|- \n| Albany Major || 1913 || Edington, Somerset<ref>{{cite book|last1=Major|first1=Albany|title=Early wars of Wessex|date=1913|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|url=https://archive.org/stream/earlywarsofwesse00majorich#page/156/mode/2up|pages=157\u2013167}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Consequences==\n[[File:England 878.svg|thumb|300px|{{center|England, 878}}]]\nThree weeks after the battle, Guthrum was baptized at [[Aller, Somerset|Aller]] in [[Somerset]] with Alfred as his sponsor.<ref name=asc878 /><ref name=asser85>Asser, ''Life'', ch. 56</ref> It is possible that the enforced conversion was an attempt by Alfred to lock Guthrum into a Christian code of ethics, hoping it would ensure the Danes' compliance with any treaties agreed to. The converted Guthrum took the baptismal name of Athelstan.<ref name=yorke176>Yorke, ''Kings and Kingdoms'', p. 176&nbsp;\u2013 177</ref>\n\nUnder the terms of the [[Treaty of Wedmore]], the converted Guthrum was required to leave Wessex and return to East Anglia. Consequently, in 879 the Viking army left Chippenham and made its way to Cirencester and remained there for a year.<ref name=asser57>Asser, ''Life'', ch. 57</ref> The following year the army went to East Anglia, where it settled.<ref name=asser60>Asser. Life. ch. 60</ref>\n\nAlso in 879, according to Asser, another Viking army sailed up the River Thames and wintered at Fulham.<ref name=asser58>Asser, ''Life'', ch. 58</ref> Over the next few years this particular Danish faction had several encounters with Alfred's forces. However, Alfred managed to contain this threat by reforming his military and setting up a system of fortified cities, known as ''burghs'' or [[burh]]s.<ref name=yorke176 />\n\nIn 885 Asser reports that the Viking army that had settled in East Anglia had broken ''in a most insolent manner'' the peace they had established with Alfred, although Guthrum is not mentioned.<ref name=asser72>Asser, ''Life'', ch. 72</ref> Guthrum reigned as king in East Anglia until his death in 890, and although this period was not always peaceful he was not considered a threat.<ref name=yorke176 /><ref name=asc890>ASC 890. English translation at [http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/657/pg657.html Project Gutenberg]</ref>\n\nIn 886, the Treaty of Alfred and Guthrum defined the boundaries of their two kingdoms. The kingdom of Mercia was divided up, with part going to Alfred's Wessex and the other part to Guthrum's East Anglia.<ref name=att96>[https://archive.org/stream/lawsofearliesten00grea#page/96/mode/2up The treaty of Alfred and Guthrum] in Attenborough's ''The laws of the earliest English kings'', pp. 96-101. Retrieved 28 January 2014</ref> The agreement also defined the social classes of Danish East Anglia and their equivalents in Wessex. It tried to provide a framework that would minimize conflict and regulate commerce between the two peoples.<ref name=abels165>Abels, ''Alfred the Great: War, Kingship and Culture in Anglo-Saxon England'', pp. 165-67</ref> It is not clear how seriously Guthrum took his conversion to Christianity, but he was the first of the Danish rulers of the English kingdoms to mint coins on the Alfredian model, under his baptismal name of Athelstan. By the end of the 9th century, all of the Anglo-Danish rulers were minting coins too. By the 10th century, the Anglo-Saxon model of kingship seems to have been universally adopted by the Anglo-Danish leadership.<ref name=abels165 />\n\nAfter the defeat of Guthrum at the Battle of Edington, Alfred's reforms to military obligations in Wessex made it increasingly difficult for the Vikings to raid successfully. By 896 the Vikings gave up with some going to East Anglia and others going to Northumbria. It was under Alfred that the Viking threat was contained. However, the system of military reforms and the [[Burghal Hidage]] introduced by [[Edward the Elder]] enabled Alfred's successors to retake control of the lands occupied in the [[Danelaw|North of England]] by the Danes.<ref name=horspool>Horspool, ''Why Alfred Burnt the Cakes'', pp. 104-110</ref><ref name=asc896>ASC 896, ASC 897. English translation at [http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/657/pg657.html Project Gutenberg]</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==The battle in fiction==\nThe battle features in several historical novels and dramas:\n* ''The Marsh King'', by [[C. Walter Hodges]]\n* ''The Raven and the Cross'', a children's television serial\n* ''[[The Ballad of the White Horse]]'', by [[G. K. Chesterton]] (who also wrote about the battle in ''Ethandune'', collected in ''Alarms and Discursions'')\n* ''[[The Last Kingdom]]'', by [[Bernard Cornwell]] pages 166-169\n* ''[[The Last Kingdom (TV series)|The Last Kingdom]]'', Season 1, Episode 8 in the television series based on Bernard Cornwell's novels\n* ''[[Sarum (novel)|Sarum]]'' by [[Edward Rutherfurd]]\n* ''[[Flesh and Bones of Frome Selwood and Wessex]]'', by [[Annette Burkitt]], pages 361-379, Hobnob Press 2017\n\n==See also==\n* Viking [[Siege of Paris (885\u201386)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://asc.jebbo.co.uk/a/a-L.html|title=The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle: An Electronic Edition (Vol 1) literary edition|\npublisher=Tony Jebson|accessdate=4 March 2012}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://domesdaymap.co.uk/|title=Domesday Map Online|publisher=Hull University|accessdate=4 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321162208/http://domesdaymap.co.uk/|archive-date=21 March 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Abels|first=Richard P|title=Alfred the Great: War, Kingship and Culture in Anglo-Saxon England|publisher=Routledge|location=Abingdon, Oxon|year=1998|isbn=0-582-04048-5}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Asser |authorlink=Asser |contribution=Life of King Alfred|editor-first=Simon|editor-last=Keynes |editor2-first=Michael |editor2-last=Lapidge |title=Alfred the Great: Asser's Life of King Alfred & Other Contemporary Sources |publisher=Penguin Classics |year=1983|isbn=978-0-14-044409-4}}\n*{{Cite book|editor-last=Attenborough|editor-first=F.L. Tr|title=The laws of the earliest English kings|publisher=Cambridge University Press\n|location=Cambridge|year=1922}}\n* {{Cite book|editor-last=Brayley|editor-first=Edward Wedlake|title=The graphic and Historical Illustrator|year=1834|publisher=J.Chidle|location=London}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=16071|publisher= British History Online|title=A History of the County of Wiltshire: Volume 8: Warminster, Westbury and Whorwellsdown Hundreds|author=Crittall, Elizabeth|accessdate=22 May 2010}}\n* {{Cite book|editor-last=Garmonsway|editor-first= G. N.| title=The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle|location=London|publisher= Dent|year =1972|isbn=0-460-11624-X }}\n* {{Cite book|last=Gransden|first=Antonia|title=Historical Writing in England: c. 500 to c. 1307|isbn=0-415-15124-4 |publisher=Routledge|year=1996|location=London}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Greswell|first=William H. P.|title=The story of the Battle of Edington|publisher=The Wessex Press|location=Taunton|year=1910}}\n* {{Cite book|authorlink=David Horspool|last=Horspool|first= David|title=Why Alfred Burned the Cakes|location=London|publisher= Profile Books|year= 2006|isbn=978-1-86197-779-3}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Jones|first= Gwyn|title=A History of the Vikings|location= Oxford|publisher= Oxford University Press|year=1984|isbn=0-19-215882-1 }}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.esawyer.org.uk|title=The Electronic Sawyer an online version of the revised edition of Sawyer's Anglo-Saxon Charters section one [S 1-1602]|publisher=Kings College|location = London|last1=Kelly|first1=S.E|last2=Miller|first2=Sean|accessdate=19 December 2012}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Lavelle|first=Ryan|title=Alfred's Wars Sources and Interpretations of Anglo-Saxon Warfare in the Viking Age|publisher=Boydel Press|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-84383-569-1|year=2010}}\n* {{Cite book|last1=Lysons|first1=Daniel|last2=Lysons|first2=Samuel|title=Magna Britannia being a concise topographical account of the several counties of Great Britain. Vol. 1. Bedfordshire, Berkshire, Buckinghamshire|location=London|year=1806|publisher=T.Cadell and W.Davies}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.trin.cam.ac.uk/chartwww/New%20RegestaIntro.html|title=The New Regesta Regum Anglorum|editor=Miller, Sean|publisher=British Academy - Royal Historical Society|accessdate=4 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927003641/http://www.trin.cam.ac.uk/chartwww/New%20RegestaIntro.html|archive-date=27 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Parker|first=Joanne|title='England's Darling'|publisher=Manchester University Press|location=Manchester|year=2007|isbn=978-0-7190-7356-4}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=The Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine: 3|year=1857|publisher=Wiltshire Archaeological Society|location=Devizes, Wiltshire}}\n* {{Cite journal|title=The Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine: 4|year=1858|publisher=Wiltshire Archaeological Society|location=Devizes, Wiltshire}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.ukniwm.org.uk/server/show/conMemorial.45340/fromUkniwmSearch/1|publisher= United Kingdom National Inventory of War Memorials|title=Battle of Ethandun|accessdate=21 May 2010}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Sawyer|first= Peter|title=The Oxford Illustrated History of the Vikings. 3rd Edition|location=Oxford|publisher= OUP|year= 2001|isbn=0-19-285434-8}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Smyth|first=Alfred P.|title=King Alfred the Great|location= Oxford|publisher= Oxford University Press|year=1995|isbn=0-19-822989-5}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Smyth|first= Alfred P. |title=The Medieval Life of King Alfred the Great: A Translation and Commentary on the Text Attributed to Asser|year=2002|publisher= Paulgrave Houndmills|location=Basingstoke, Hampshire|isbn=0-333-69917-3}}\n* {{Cite book|editor-last=Stevenson|editor-first=William Henry|title=Asser's Life of King Alfred together with the annals of Saint Neots erroneously ascribed to Asser|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1904|location=Oxford}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Stevenson|first=W H|journal=The Athenaeum Journal|volume=4116|title=The Battle of Ethandun|publisher=J.C.Francis and J.E.Francis|location=London|date=15 September 1906|pages=303\u2013304}}\n* {{Cite web|last=Vergil|first=Polydore|authorlink=Polydore Vergil|editor-first=Dana F|editor-last= Sutton|title=Angelica Historia (Online Ed.)|year=1555|publisher=Hosted by University of Birmingham|url=http://www.philological.bham.ac.uk/polverg/|accessdate=5 March 2012}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Whitaker|first=John|title=The Life of Saint Neot the oldest of all brothers to King Alfred|publisher=John Joseph Stockwell|year=1809|location=London}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Yorke|first=Barbara|authorlink=Barbara Yorke|title=Kings and Kingdoms of Anglo-Saxon England|publisher=Routledge|location=London|year=1997|isbn=0-415-16639-X}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p003k9gm BBC Radio 4 Archive Programme - In Our Time: ''Alfred and the Battle of Edington'']\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Viking Invasion of England}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ethandun}}\n[[Category:870s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Wessex]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Vikings]]\n[[Category:Military history of Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Anglo-Saxons]]\n[[Category:878]]\n[[Category:9th century in England]]\n", "name_user": "Timandannetteburkitt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBattle", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Edington"}
{"title_page": "South Kilburn", "text_new": "[[File:South Kilburn Estate - geograph.org.uk - 417246.jpg|thumb|View of South Kilburn tower blocks]]\n'''South Kilburn''' is a large [[housing estate]] in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]], in the [[London Borough of Brent]].<ref name=\"Gang\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/davehillblog/2012/mar/01/youth-violence-london-westminster-brent|title=London falling: violence, feuds and fear scar the capital's heart|first=Dave|last=Hill|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=\"reDev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.homesandproperty.co.uk/property-news/why-south-kilburn-is-the-central-london-area-buyers-should-get-to-know-a123851.html|title=Fantastically well-located former 'no-go zone' getting \u00a3600m overhaul|date=11 September 2018|website=Homes and Property|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> Typical of [[brutalist]] 60's designs of [[public housing in the United Kingdom]] it is characterised by high-density housing in low-rise flats and 11 concrete [[tower block]]s. It was approved in 1959 and extended in 1963. This scheme was further developed in the late 1960s and early 1970s. The population is predominantly [[British Afro-Caribbean community|Afro-Caribbean]].\n\n==Location==\nSouth Kilburn is within the [[London Borough of Brent]], to the east/southeast of [[Queens Park tube station]], immediately south of [[Kilburn Park tube station]], north of [[Maida Hill]], and to the west of the [[Paddington Recreation Ground]]. Carlton Vale is the [[numbered street]] that separates the northern and southern parts of the estate.\n\n==Redevelopment==\nIn 2014 a massive redevelopment project was started by the [[London Borough of Brent]] to redevelop the estate, starting with the demolition of two of the 18-storey housing blocks on the estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/south-kilburn-says-goodbye-to-two-tower-blocks-as-part-of-660m-regeneration-project-1-3427969|title=South Kilburn says goodbye to two tower blocks as part of \u00a3660m regeneration project|last=King|first=Lorraine|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> This has continued with the creation of new housing blocks built to modern design quality and energy efficiency standards and owned by several different [[Housing association|housing associations]] along with infill developments owned by the local council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/10/south-kilburn-estate-brent-council-alison-brooks-architects|title=South Kilburn estate review \u2013 homes that are streets ahead|last=Moore|first=Rowan|date=10 July 2016|website=Theguardian.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> Per the plans for this regeneration scheme, the redevelopment so far has seen a net loss of social housing units as most of the new blocks replacing the demolished buildings include a number of flats for social rent (\"council housing\") along with flats for sale on the private market. The  Gloucester House and Durham Court section of the regeneration, begun by [[Telford Homes]] housing association in 2017, will see the demolition of 209 flats and their replacement with 235 new-build units, nearly half of which (133) will be for private sale.<ref name=\"reDev\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/news/west-london-news/south-kilburn-regeneration-everything-you-14360455|title=Everything you need to know about 235 new South Kilburn homes|last=Miller|first=Frederica|date=2018-03-07|website=getwestlondon|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telfordhomes-ir.london/showcase/south-kilburn/|title=South Kilburn {{!}} Telford Homes|website=www.telfordhomes-ir.london|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> The construction of market-rate flats for sale has made the area popular with real estate investors and home-buyers who see the area's central location and numerous transport links as attractive features.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homesandproperty.co.uk/property-news/why-south-kilburn-is-the-central-london-area-buyers-should-get-to-know-a123851.html|title=Fantastically well-located former 'no-go zone' getting \u00a3600m overhaul|date=2018-09-11|website=Homes and Property|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, inhabitants of the newly built Merle Court (opened in 2012) were forced to move due to design problems in the building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/merle-court-evictions-1-6029978|title=Defects in South Kilburn block results in all occupiers forced to move home|last=Raffray|first=Nathalie|website=Kilburn Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> Several months later the mandatory balloting procedure of residents for Phase 2 of the South Kilburn redevelopment scheme was met with a campaign by some local residents to extend the ballot to all 8,000 residents, many of whom, in anticipation of future demolition, are settled on the estate as residents in temporary accommodation, and who, Brent Council argues, do not need to be included under the [[Greater London Authority]]'s rules on estate regeneration balloting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/petition-as-thousands-cannot-vote-on-south-kilburn-regeneration-ballot-1-6318530|title=Petition launched to stop South Kilburn regeneration ballot so 8,000 others can take part|last=Raffray|first=Nathalie|website=Kilburn Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>  \n\n==Problems with crime==\n[[File:William Dunbar House, Kilburn.jpg|thumb|200px|William Dunbar House]]\nSouth Kilburn has long been plagued by [[crime]], the streets and blocks that characterise the dense sprawl of housing being the sight of numerous shootings and a drug trade controlled by various [[gang]]s, including the notorious \u00a3R.<ref name=\"Gang\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-148377901/be-brave-plea-over-gun-killer-in-brief|title='Be Brave' Plea over Gun Killer; in Brief\" - The Evening Standard (London, England), July 19, 2006 - Online Research Library: Questia Reader|website=Questia.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialaffairsunit.org.uk/blog/archives/001062.php|title=The Social Affairs Unit - Web Review: The Murder of Toni-Ann Byfield: if future such cases are to be prevented the practice of bringing young children into the UK to be educated / exploited in a welfare-rich country must be challenged, argues Lilian Pizzichini|website=www.socialaffairsunit.org.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gangWar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/innocent-queen-s-park-electrician-was-gunned-down-in-revenge-for-gangland-murder-of-south-kilburn-man-1-1403791|title=Innocent Queen's Park electrician was gunned down in revenge for gangland murder of South Kilburn man|first=Ben|last=Bloom|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The gangs of South Kilburn have been known to have an ongoing rivalry with gangs from the nearby [[Mozart Estate]], which has resulted in numerous shootings, stabbings and [[kidnapping]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2013/08/westminster-you-dont-see|title=The Westminster you don\u2019t see|website=Newstatesman.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Gang\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-15126415|title='Postcode' wars blighting estate|first=Kevin|last=Young|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"gangWar\" /> The rivalry has been reported to be a typical \"postcode war\",<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-15126415</ref> as South Kilburn is part of NW6 while Mozart Estate is in W9 and in the [[City of Westminster]].\n\n===2007 raid===\nOn 18 April 2007, 500 [[police]], including firearms officers, raided the estate in a series of dawn raids after a months-long [[sting operation]] where members of a gang known as F.A.C. (Fire Arms Cartel) had been selling [[gun]]s to undercover police officers.<ref name=\"Raid\">{{cite web|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/500-police-storm-homes-to-smash-gang-that-terrorised-an-estate-7191028.html|title=500 police storm homes to smash gang that terrorised an estate|date=18 April 2007|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisislocallondon.co.uk/news/1337254.17-arrests-on-crime-ridden-estate/|title=17 arrests on crime-ridden estate|website=This Is Local London|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> Numerous arrests were made resulting in prosecutions with claims that the police had 'smashed' an 'untouchable gang'.<ref name=\"Raid\" />\nAlthough crime levels subsequently fell to some extent, there were similar raids in 2011 when 250 police officers once again stormed South Kilburn Estate in a co-ordinated drugs raid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/250-police-storm-homes-in-south-kilburn-drugs-raid-1-896641|title=250 police storm homes in South Kilburn drugs raid|first=Kate|last=Ferguson|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The gang rivalry between South Kilburn and Mozart Estate has continued with numerous gang fights as well as the shooting of innocent victim Daniel Omari Smith, gunned down in 2010 in a [[KFC]] in a case of mistaken identity.<ref name=\"gangWar\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/estate-gangs-clash-in-kilburn-1-859434|title=Estate gangs clash in Kilburn|first=Glenn|last=McMahon|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-14582126|title=Man in electrician murder charge|date=18 August 2011|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Bbc.co.uk}}</ref> In 2013, mother of one Sabrina Moss, was killed in a takeaway shop on Kilburn High Road while celebrating her 24th birthday when she was hit by bullets from a [[MAC-10]] submachine gun, intended for South Kilburn gang members from the F.A.C. gang who were also in the takeaway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-29180584|title=Teacher killers jailed for 37 years|date=12 September 2014|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"MacMoss\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/pair-injured-in-sabrina-moss-murder-allegedly-south-kilburn-gang-members-1-3666276|title=Pair injured in Sabrina Moss murder allegedly South Kilburn gang members|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> Her friend as well as two South Kilburn gang members were also hit by bullets and injured in the attack which was perpetrated by members of the Kensal Green Boys gang who were involved in a long-running feud with gangs from South Kilburn Estate.<ref name=\"MacMoss\" />\n\n===Mohanna Abdhou murder===\nIn May 2017, Mohanna Abdhou, a 20-year-old woman, was shot and killed while hanging out with friends on South Kilburn Estate outside Dickens House.<ref name=\"Mohanna\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/30/woman-shot-dead-in-kilburn-was-innocent-bystander-witnesses-say|title=Woman shot dead in Kilburn was innocent bystander, witnesses say|last=Khomami|first=Nadia|date=30 May 2017|website=Theguardian.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The intended targets were probably a group of young men from the estate who managed to escape being shot while Mohanna, who had no involvement with gangs, was tragically hit by a bullet in the stomach and died.<ref name=\"Mohanna\" /> Once again, this killing was connected by police and prosecutors to the tit for tat violence between local gangs in and around the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-43660841|title=Woman killed by stray 'gang war' bullet|date=5 April 2018|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The [[Gang#Gang violence|gang war]] between Mozart Estate and South Kilburn Estate continues despite community and local government action.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/crime-court/south-kilburn-teenager-arrested-in-connection-with-mozart-estate-drive-by-shooting-1-1161888|title=South Kilburn teenager arrested in connection with Mozart Estate drive-by shooting|last=King|first=Lorraine|website=Hampstead Highgate Express|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe area continues to be effected by its history of gang violence and drug dealing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/local-news/gang-arrests-made-notorious-estate-5970635|title=Gang arrests made in notorious estate in Kilburn|last1=Bewley|first1=by Hannah|last2=00:00|first2=24 Jan 2013Updated17:08|date=24 January 2013|website=mylondon|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/drugs-and-deadly-weapons-found-hidden-in-bushes-in-south-kilburn-1-4538883|title=Drugs and deadly weapons found hidden in bushes in South Kilburn|last=King|first=Lorraine|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Housing corruption===\nA scheme started by the South Kilburn Partnership to redevelop the estate, was accused of corruption in 2010 when \u00a350million allocated for the estate's redevelopment went missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/regeneration-boss-promises-to-deliver-1-603630|title=Regeneration boss promises to deliver|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Thanks London.JPG|thumb|200px|A photo taken from a 16th floor flat in the estate, showing adjacent expensive terraced houses on Kilburn Park Road]]\nSouth Kilburn features as a setting in award-winning author [[Zadie Smith]]'s novel ''[[White Teeth]]''.<ref name=\"reDev\" /> It is also featured in a short story published in ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', titled \"The Rape of Dina\", recounting the true story of a murder which took place on the estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/mvn7ab/the-rape-of-dina|title='The Rape Of Dina' by Gabriel Krauze|first=Gabriel Krauze, Illustrations: Krent|last=Able|date=28 October 2015|website=Vice.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stonebridge, London|Stonebridge Estate]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coords|51.530|-0.197|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Kilburn, London]]\n[[Category:Housing estates in London]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:South Kilburn Estate - geograph.org.uk - 417246.jpg|thumb|View of South Kilburn tower blocks]]\n'''South Kilburn''' is a large [[housing estate]] in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]], in the [[London Borough of Brent]].<ref name=\"Gang\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/davehillblog/2012/mar/01/youth-violence-london-westminster-brent|title=London falling: violence, feuds and fear scar the capital's heart|first=Dave|last=Hill|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=\"reDev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.homesandproperty.co.uk/property-news/why-south-kilburn-is-the-central-london-area-buyers-should-get-to-know-a123851.html|title=Fantastically well-located former 'no-go zone' getting \u00a3600m overhaul|date=11 September 2018|website=Homes and Property|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> Typical of [[brutalist]] 60's designs of [[public housing in the United Kingdom]] it is characterised by high-density housing in low-rise flats and 11 concrete [[tower block]]s. It was approved in 1959 and extended in 1963. This scheme was further developed in the late 1960s and early 1970s. The population is predominantly [[British Afro-Caribbean community|Afro-Caribbean]].\n\n==Location==\nSouth Kilburn is within the [[London Borough of Brent]], to the east/southeast of [[Queens Park tube station]], immediately south of [[Kilburn Park tube station]], north of [[Maida Hill]], and to the west of the [[Paddington Recreation Ground]]. Carlton Vale is the [[numbered street]] that separates the northern and southern parts of the estate.\n\n==Redevelopment==\nIn 2014 a massive redevelopment project was started by the [[London Borough of Brent]] to redevelop the estate, starting with the demolition of two of the 18-storey housing blocks on the estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/south-kilburn-says-goodbye-to-two-tower-blocks-as-part-of-660m-regeneration-project-1-3427969|title=South Kilburn says goodbye to two tower blocks as part of \u00a3660m regeneration project|last=King|first=Lorraine|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> This has continued with the creation of new housing blocks built to modern design quality and energy efficiency standards and owned by several different [[Housing association|housing associations]] along with infill developments owned by the local council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/10/south-kilburn-estate-brent-council-alison-brooks-architects|title=South Kilburn estate review \u2013 homes that are streets ahead|last=Moore|first=Rowan|date=10 July 2016|website=Theguardian.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> Per the plans for this regeneration scheme, the redevelopment so far has seen a net loss of social housing units as most of the new blocks replacing the demolished buildings include a number of flats for social rent (\"council housing\") along with flats for sale on the private market. The  Gloucester House and Durham Court section of the regeneration, begun by [[Telford Homes]] housing association in 2017, will see the demolition of 209 flats and their replacement with 235 new-build units, nearly half of which (133) will be for private sale.<ref name=\"reDev\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/news/west-london-news/south-kilburn-regeneration-everything-you-14360455|title=Everything you need to know about 235 new South Kilburn homes|last=Miller|first=Frederica|date=2018-03-07|website=getwestlondon|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telfordhomes-ir.london/showcase/south-kilburn/|title=South Kilburn {{!}} Telford Homes|website=www.telfordhomes-ir.london|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> The construction of market-rate flats for sale has made the area popular with real estate investors and home-buyers who see the area's central location and numerous transport links as attractive features.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homesandproperty.co.uk/property-news/why-south-kilburn-is-the-central-london-area-buyers-should-get-to-know-a123851.html|title=Fantastically well-located former 'no-go zone' getting \u00a3600m overhaul|date=2018-09-11|website=Homes and Property|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, inhabitants of the newly built Merle Court (opened in 2012) were forced to move due to design problems in the building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/merle-court-evictions-1-6029978|title=Defects in South Kilburn block results in all occupiers forced to move home|last=Raffray|first=Nathalie|website=Kilburn Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> Several months later the mandatory balloting procedure of residents for Phase 2 of the South Kilburn redevelopment scheme was met with a campaign by some local residents to extend the ballot to all 8,000 residents, many of whom, in anticipation of future demolition, are settled on the estate as residents in temporary accommodation, and who, Brent Council argues, do not need to be included under the [[Greater London Authority]]'s rules on estate regeneration balloting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/petition-as-thousands-cannot-vote-on-south-kilburn-regeneration-ballot-1-6318530|title=Petition launched to stop South Kilburn regeneration ballot so 8,000 others can take part|last=Raffray|first=Nathalie|website=Kilburn Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>  \n\n==Problems with crime==\n[[File:William Dunbar House, Kilburn.jpg|thumb|200px|William Dunbar House]]\nSouth Kilburn has long been plagued by [[crime]], the streets and blocks that characterise the dense sprawl of housing being the sight of numerous shootings and a drug trade controlled by various [[gang]]s, including the notorious [[\u00a3R]].<ref name=\"Gang\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-148377901/be-brave-plea-over-gun-killer-in-brief|title='Be Brave' Plea over Gun Killer; in Brief\" - The Evening Standard (London, England), July 19, 2006 - Online Research Library: Questia Reader|website=Questia.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialaffairsunit.org.uk/blog/archives/001062.php|title=The Social Affairs Unit - Web Review: The Murder of Toni-Ann Byfield: if future such cases are to be prevented the practice of bringing young children into the UK to be educated / exploited in a welfare-rich country must be challenged, argues Lilian Pizzichini|website=www.socialaffairsunit.org.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gangWar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/innocent-queen-s-park-electrician-was-gunned-down-in-revenge-for-gangland-murder-of-south-kilburn-man-1-1403791|title=Innocent Queen's Park electrician was gunned down in revenge for gangland murder of South Kilburn man|first=Ben|last=Bloom|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The gangs of South Kilburn have been known to have an ongoing rivalry with gangs from the nearby [[Mozart Estate]], which has resulted in numerous shootings, stabbings and [[kidnapping]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2013/08/westminster-you-dont-see|title=The Westminster you don\u2019t see|website=Newstatesman.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Gang\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-15126415|title='Postcode' wars blighting estate|first=Kevin|last=Young|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"gangWar\" /> The rivalry has been reported to be a typical \"postcode war\",<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-15126415</ref> as South Kilburn is part of NW6 while Mozart Estate is in W9 and in the [[City of Westminster]].\n\n===2007 raid===\nOn 18 April 2007, 500 [[police]], including firearms officers, raided the estate in a series of dawn raids after a months-long [[sting operation]] where members of a gang known as F.A.C. (Fire Arms Cartel) had been selling [[gun]]s to undercover police officers.<ref name=\"Raid\">{{cite web|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/news/500-police-storm-homes-to-smash-gang-that-terrorised-an-estate-7191028.html|title=500 police storm homes to smash gang that terrorised an estate|date=18 April 2007|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisislocallondon.co.uk/news/1337254.17-arrests-on-crime-ridden-estate/|title=17 arrests on crime-ridden estate|website=This Is Local London|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> Numerous arrests were made resulting in prosecutions with claims that the police had 'smashed' an 'untouchable gang'.<ref name=\"Raid\" />\nAlthough crime levels subsequently fell to some extent, there were similar raids in 2011 when 250 police officers once again stormed South Kilburn Estate in a co-ordinated drugs raid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/250-police-storm-homes-in-south-kilburn-drugs-raid-1-896641|title=250 police storm homes in South Kilburn drugs raid|first=Kate|last=Ferguson|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The gang rivalry between South Kilburn and Mozart Estate has continued with numerous gang fights as well as the shooting of innocent victim Daniel Omari Smith, gunned down in 2010 in a [[KFC]] in a case of mistaken identity.<ref name=\"gangWar\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/estate-gangs-clash-in-kilburn-1-859434|title=Estate gangs clash in Kilburn|first=Glenn|last=McMahon|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-14582126|title=Man in electrician murder charge|date=18 August 2011|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Bbc.co.uk}}</ref> In 2013, mother of one Sabrina Moss, was killed in a takeaway shop on Kilburn High Road while celebrating her 24th birthday when she was hit by bullets from a [[MAC-10]] submachine gun, intended for South Kilburn gang members from the F.A.C. gang who were also in the takeaway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-29180584|title=Teacher killers jailed for 37 years|date=12 September 2014|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"MacMoss\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/pair-injured-in-sabrina-moss-murder-allegedly-south-kilburn-gang-members-1-3666276|title=Pair injured in Sabrina Moss murder allegedly South Kilburn gang members|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> Her friend as well as two South Kilburn gang members were also hit by bullets and injured in the attack which was perpetrated by members of the Kensal Green Boys gang who were involved in a long-running feud with gangs from South Kilburn Estate.<ref name=\"MacMoss\" />\n\n===Mohanna Abdhou murder===\nIn May 2017, Mohanna Abdhou, a 20-year-old woman, was shot and killed while hanging out with friends on South Kilburn Estate outside Dickens House.<ref name=\"Mohanna\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/30/woman-shot-dead-in-kilburn-was-innocent-bystander-witnesses-say|title=Woman shot dead in Kilburn was innocent bystander, witnesses say|last=Khomami|first=Nadia|date=30 May 2017|website=Theguardian.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The intended targets were probably a group of young men from the estate who managed to escape being shot while Mohanna, who had no involvement with gangs, was tragically hit by a bullet in the stomach and died.<ref name=\"Mohanna\" /> Once again, this killing was connected by police and prosecutors to the tit for tat violence between local gangs in and around the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-43660841|title=Woman killed by stray 'gang war' bullet|date=5 April 2018|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The [[Gang#Gang violence|gang war]] between Mozart Estate and South Kilburn Estate continues despite community and local government action.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/crime-court/south-kilburn-teenager-arrested-in-connection-with-mozart-estate-drive-by-shooting-1-1161888|title=South Kilburn teenager arrested in connection with Mozart Estate drive-by shooting|last=King|first=Lorraine|website=Hampstead Highgate Express|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe area continues to be effected by its history of gang violence and drug dealing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/local-news/gang-arrests-made-notorious-estate-5970635|title=Gang arrests made in notorious estate in Kilburn|last1=Bewley|first1=by Hannah|last2=00:00|first2=24 Jan 2013Updated17:08|date=24 January 2013|website=mylondon|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/drugs-and-deadly-weapons-found-hidden-in-bushes-in-south-kilburn-1-4538883|title=Drugs and deadly weapons found hidden in bushes in South Kilburn|last=King|first=Lorraine|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Housing corruption===\nA scheme started by the South Kilburn Partnership to redevelop the estate, was accused of corruption in 2010 when \u00a350million allocated for the estate's redevelopment went missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/regeneration-boss-promises-to-deliver-1-603630|title=Regeneration boss promises to deliver|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Thanks London.JPG|thumb|200px|A photo taken from a 16th floor flat in the estate, showing adjacent expensive terraced houses on Kilburn Park Road]]\nSouth Kilburn features as a setting in award-winning author [[Zadie Smith]]'s novel ''[[White Teeth]]''.<ref name=\"reDev\" /> It is also featured in a short story published in ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', titled \"The Rape of Dina\", recounting the true story of a murder which took place on the estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/mvn7ab/the-rape-of-dina|title='The Rape Of Dina' by Gabriel Krauze|first=Gabriel Krauze, Illustrations: Krent|last=Able|date=28 October 2015|website=Vice.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Stonebridge, London|Stonebridge Estate]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coords|51.530|-0.197|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Kilburn, London]]\n[[Category:Housing estates in London]]\n", "name_user": "Yunshui", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/\u00a3Rclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Kilburn"}
{"title_page": "Ice City Boyz", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Ice City Boyz\n| image               = IceCityBoyz.png\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Church End, Brent|Church End]], [[London]], [[England]].\n| genre               = [[British hip hop]]\n| years_active        = 2009\u2013present\n| label               = Zino Records\n| associated_acts     = \n| current_members     = [[Nines (rapper)|Nines]]<br/> Skrapz<br> Trapstar Toxic<br/> Likkle T<br/> J Styles<br/> Fatz<br/> Keyz<br/> Streetz <br/>Inch <br/>Fundz <br/>Jambo <br/>Trappy<br>Storm\n| past_members        = Zino (Deceased)\n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Ice City Boyz (ICB)''' (colloquially referred to as '''Church Road Soldiers''' and '''CrimeScene Boyz''') is a British [[hip hop music|hip hop]] [[musical collective|collective]] from [[Church End, Brent|Church End]], [[London]].\n\n==Background==\nThe rap collective has been around since the mid 2000s and started making music towards the end of the decade. Most members of the group come from the [[Church End Estate]]. The most successful artist from the group consists of [[Nines (rapper)|Nines]]. Other artists in the group include Likkle T, Skrapz, J Styles, Fatz, Keyz, Trapstar Toxic, Streetz, Inch, Supa, Fundz, Jambo and others.<ref name=\"rapperwar\">{{cite web|url=http://ibtimes.co.uk/london-rapper-war-revealed-harlesden-mc-nines-cbiz-mugging-another-bodybag-1549760|title= London rapper war revealed: Harlesden MC Nines, the Cbiz mugging and another bodybag|publisher= IBN Times |accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref> The success of Nines has led to other members of the gang to take music more seriously. \n\nTrapster Toxic released the single \"Life I Live\" in November 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/trapstar-toxic-drops-cold-visuals-for-life-i-live|title=Trapstar Toxic drops cold visuals for \"Life I Live\" |website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture}}</ref> J Stylez, Fatz and Streetz released the single \"Statement\" in April 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ice-city-boyz-statement|title= PREMIERE: Ice City Boyz make a \"Statement\" with mad new video  |website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n===U.S.G.===\nSince early 2000, Ice City Boyz have been involved in a [[Gang warfare|gang wars]] with Stonebridge gang and rap collective [[U.S.G.]], whose prominent member is [[K Koke]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/london-grime-war-police-fear-stonebridge-church-road-feud-could-boil-over-after-big-keyz-jacked-1582247|title=London grime war: Police fear Stonebridge and Church Road feud could boil over after Big Keyz jacked|date=September 20, 2016|website=International Business Times UK}}</ref> The rivalry has been ongoing and Nines has taken shots at K Koke with the reference \"I ain't laying down my weapons\" in his song \"[[Trapper of the Year (song)|Trapper of the Year]]\" released as a [[sneak diss]] referencing Koke's song \"[[Lay Down Your Weapons]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/lay-down-your-weapons-feat-rita-ora-single/961651190|title=Lay Down Your Weapons (feat. Rita Ora) - Single by K Koke|via=music.apple.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grimebeef.com/k-koke-vs-nines/|title=K Koke vs Nines|date=July 10, 2017}}</ref> K Koke retalliated by mentioning Nine's brother who was murdered in an alleged gangland attack on the track \"Listen Likkle Man\".<ref>{{cite web |title='Revenge killing' gunman jailed |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/8148718.stm |website=BBC News |accessdate=21 June 2019 |date=13 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_hrwWo2mGR0|title=What's Beef? (Nines Vs K Koke, Chip Vs Bugzy, Dot Rotten Vs P Money, Tobz Vs Blittz)|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> In September 2019, ICB member Skrapz was charged with perverting the court of justice in relation to the murder of U.S.G. member Smallz and after being stabbed in prison he was released with no further action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/rapper-charged-with-craig-small-death-1-6284351|title=Craig Small shooting: Harlesden grime artist Skrapz charged with perverting course of justice as three more men arrested in connection with Wembley killing|first=Nathalie|last=Raffray|website=Kilburn Times}}</ref>\n\n===\u00a3R===\nICB are also involved in a rivalry with C Biz's rap gang \"\u00a3R\" ('''Eating Right''' stylised as \u00a3ating Right). It was alleged that a member of ICB was posing with a gold chain and watch that was apparently stolen from C Biz of \u00a3R.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/bad-boys-british-grime-161100306.html|title=Who are the bad boys of British grime?|website=uk.news.yahoo.com}}</ref> Nines published a video on his social media with a handful of gold jewellery, including an Audemars Piguet watch that was supposedly stolen from C-Biz. It has been reported that the pair have a history of rivalry relating to the killing of Zino, Nines's brother who was murdered in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/london-rapper-war-revealed-harlesden-mc-nines-cbiz-mugging-another-bodybag-1549760|title=London rapper war revealed: Harlesden MC Nines, the Cbiz mugging and another bodybag|date=March 18, 2016|website=International Business Times UK}}</ref> As a result, a drive-by shooting happened in the church road estate which resulted in the death of Oliver Tetlow in what was said to be a case of mistaken identity. This garnered the attention of former prime minister [[David Cameron]] who condemned the shooting. C Biz and six other men were bailed for the shooting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/oliver-tetlow-shooting-seven-arrested-bailed-pm-condemns-tragic-harlesden-murder-1549906|title=Oliver Tetlow shooting: CBIZ and six men bailed as David Cameron condemns tragic Harlesden murder|date=March 16, 2016|website=International Business Times UK}}</ref>\n\n===Trapstar Toxic===\nAdetokunbo Ajibola (better known by his stage name '''Trapstar Toxic''') was caught out by his song lyrics which revealed him selling drugs. It was reported the police used his lyrics from his single \"Out Ere\" in court. This lead to a raid in his home in Willesden in April 2008, when police found \u00a330,000 of drugs. They described the scene as a \"drugs preparation factory\" and also seized \u00a313,000 in cash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/jailed-rapper-caught-out-by-song-lyrics-revealing-drugdealing-lifestyle-a4081871.html|title=Jailed rapper caught out by song lyrics about drugs|date=March 4, 2019|website=Evening Standard}}</ref> Toxic pleaded guilty to the offences June 27 2018, and was jailed for five years at Harrow Crown Court on 1 March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/west-london-news/trapstar-toxic-london-rapper-jailed-15910725|title=Willesden rapper who bragged about drug dealing in video jailed|first=Sam|last=Truelove|date=March 2, 2019|website=getwestlondon}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:English hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Hip hop collectives]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:Underground rappers]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2009]]\n[[Category:London street gangs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Ice City Boyz\n| image               = IceCityBoyz.png\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Church End, Brent|Church End]], [[London]], [[England]].\n| genre               = [[British hip hop]]\n| years_active        = 2009\u2013present\n| label               = Zino Records\n| associated_acts     = \n| current_members     = [[Nines (rapper)|Nines]]<br/> Skrapz<br> Trapstar Toxic<br/> Likkle T<br/> J Styles<br/> Fatz<br/> Keyz<br/> Streetz <br/>Inch <br/>Fundz <br/>Jambo <br/>Trappy<br>Storm\n| past_members        = Zino (Deceased)\n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Ice City Boyz (ICB)''' (colloquially referred to as '''Church Road Soldiers''' and '''CrimeScene Boyz''') is a British [[hip hop music|hip hop]] [[musical collective|collective]] from [[Church End, Brent|Church End]], [[London]].\n\n==Background==\nThe rap collective has been around since the mid 2000s and started making music towards the end of the decade. Most members of the group come from the [[Church End Estate]]. The most successful artist from the group consists of [[Nines (rapper)|Nines]]. Other artists in the group include Likkle T, Skrapz, J Styles, Fatz, Keyz, Trapstar Toxic, Streetz, Inch, Supa, Fundz, Jambo and others.<ref name=\"rapperwar\">{{cite web|url=http://ibtimes.co.uk/london-rapper-war-revealed-harlesden-mc-nines-cbiz-mugging-another-bodybag-1549760|title= London rapper war revealed: Harlesden MC Nines, the Cbiz mugging and another bodybag|publisher= IBN Times |accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref> The success of Nines has led to other members of the gang to take music more seriously. \n\nTrapster Toxic released the single \"Life I Live\" in November 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/trapstar-toxic-drops-cold-visuals-for-life-i-live|title=Trapstar Toxic drops cold visuals for \"Life I Live\" |website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture}}</ref> J Stylez, Fatz and Streetz released the single \"Statement\" in April 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/ice-city-boyz-statement|title= PREMIERE: Ice City Boyz make a \"Statement\" with mad new video  |website=GRM Daily - Grime, Rap music and Culture}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n===U.S.G.===\nSince early 2000, Ice City Boyz have been involved in a [[Gang warfare|gang wars]] with Stonebridge gang and rap collective [[U.S.G.]], whose prominent member is [[K Koke]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/london-grime-war-police-fear-stonebridge-church-road-feud-could-boil-over-after-big-keyz-jacked-1582247|title=London grime war: Police fear Stonebridge and Church Road feud could boil over after Big Keyz jacked|date=September 20, 2016|website=International Business Times UK}}</ref> The rivalry has been ongoing and Nines has taken shots at K Koke with the reference \"I ain't laying down my weapons\" in his song \"[[Trapper of the Year (song)|Trapper of the Year]]\" released as a [[sneak diss]] referencing Koke's song \"[[Lay Down Your Weapons]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/gb/album/lay-down-your-weapons-feat-rita-ora-single/961651190|title=Lay Down Your Weapons (feat. Rita Ora) - Single by K Koke|via=music.apple.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grimebeef.com/k-koke-vs-nines/|title=K Koke vs Nines|date=July 10, 2017}}</ref> K Koke retalliated by mentioning Nine's brother who was murdered in an alleged gangland attack on the track \"Listen Likkle Man\".<ref>{{cite web |title='Revenge killing' gunman jailed |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/8148718.stm |website=BBC News |accessdate=21 June 2019 |date=13 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_hrwWo2mGR0|title=What's Beef? (Nines Vs K Koke, Chip Vs Bugzy, Dot Rotten Vs P Money, Tobz Vs Blittz)|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> In September 2019, ICB member Skrapz was charged with perverting the court of justice in relation to the murder of U.S.G. member Smallz and after being stabbed in prison he was released with no further action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/rapper-charged-with-craig-small-death-1-6284351|title=Craig Small shooting: Harlesden grime artist Skrapz charged with perverting course of justice as three more men arrested in connection with Wembley killing|first=Nathalie|last=Raffray|website=Kilburn Times}}</ref>\n\n===\u00a3R===\nICB are also involved in a rivalry with C Biz's rap gang \"[[\u00a3R]]\" ('''Eating Right''' stylised as \u00a3ating Right). It was alleged that a member of ICB was posing with a gold chain and watch that was apparently stolen from C Biz of \u00a3R.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/bad-boys-british-grime-161100306.html|title=Who are the bad boys of British grime?|website=uk.news.yahoo.com}}</ref> Nines published a video on his social media with a handful of gold jewellery, including an Audemars Piguet watch that was supposedly stolen from C-Biz. It has been reported that the pair have a history of rivalry relating to the killing of Zino, Nines's brother who was murdered in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/london-rapper-war-revealed-harlesden-mc-nines-cbiz-mugging-another-bodybag-1549760|title=London rapper war revealed: Harlesden MC Nines, the Cbiz mugging and another bodybag|date=March 18, 2016|website=International Business Times UK}}</ref> As a result, a drive-by shooting happened in the church road estate which resulted in the death of Oliver Tetlow in what was said to be a case of mistaken identity. This garnered the attention of former prime minister [[David Cameron]] who condemned the shooting. C Biz and six other men were bailed for the shooting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/oliver-tetlow-shooting-seven-arrested-bailed-pm-condemns-tragic-harlesden-murder-1549906|title=Oliver Tetlow shooting: CBIZ and six men bailed as David Cameron condemns tragic Harlesden murder|date=March 16, 2016|website=International Business Times UK}}</ref>\n\n===Trapstar Toxic===\nAdetokunbo Ajibola (better known by his stage name '''Trapstar Toxic''') was caught out by his song lyrics which revealed him selling drugs. It was reported the police used his lyrics from his single \"Out Ere\" in court. This lead to a raid in his home in Willesden in April 2008, when police found \u00a330,000 of drugs. They described the scene as a \"drugs preparation factory\" and also seized \u00a313,000 in cash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/jailed-rapper-caught-out-by-song-lyrics-revealing-drugdealing-lifestyle-a4081871.html|title=Jailed rapper caught out by song lyrics about drugs|date=March 4, 2019|website=Evening Standard}}</ref> Toxic pleaded guilty to the offences June 27 2018, and was jailed for five years at Harrow Crown Court on 1 March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/west-london-news/trapstar-toxic-london-rapper-jailed-15910725|title=Willesden rapper who bragged about drug dealing in video jailed|first=Sam|last=Truelove|date=March 2, 2019|website=getwestlondon}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:English hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Hip hop collectives]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:Underground rappers]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2009]]\n[[Category:London street gangs]]\n", "name_user": "Yunshui", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/\u00a3Rclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ice_City_Boyz"}
{"title_page": "Harrow Road Boyz", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = HRB\n| image               = HarrowRoadBoyz_logo.png\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Queen's Park, London|Queen's Park]], [[London]], England\n| genre               = [[British hip hop]]\n| years_active        = 2010\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| current_members     = [[Fredo (rapper)|Fredo]]<br>Ratlin<br>Rugrat<br>Mystro<br>Grizly<br>Rebellion<br>Belly<br>Jah Vinci\n| past_members        = Muscle Gotti (deceased)<ref>https://www.mylondon.news/news/west-london-news/man-being-chased-police-wembley-18034085</ref>\n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Harrow Road Boyz (HRB)''', also referred to as the '''Mozart gang''', is a British [[hip hop music|hip hop]] [[Musical collective|collective]] and [[street gang]] from [[Queen's Park, London|Queen's Park]], [[London]]. Most members of the group are from the notorious Mozart Estate located between Queens Park and [[Ladbroke Grove]].\n\n==History==\nThe name 'Mozart' refers to the gangs territory, the Mozart estate between Ladbroke Grove and Queens Park. One of the earliest members out of the gang who started rapping was '''Ratlin''' (born July 20, 1990). Ratlin's commercial success came with the mixtape ''Youngest In Charge'' which was released in August, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.datpiff.com/RATLIN-CORLEONE-Youngest-In-Charge-mixtape.238789.html|title=Youngest In Charge Mixtape by RATLIN CORLEONE Hosted by MYKA MILLION|website=www.datpiff.com}}</ref> He has since released numerous mixtapes including ''Summertime In Mexico'' and its sequel ''Summertime In Mexico 2'' both of which have accumulated over one million views on YouTube. Ratlin used to play for the local football team [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at 11.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/a3bvnk/fredo-third-avenue-album-interview-2019|title=Fredo: \u201cI\u2019ve Spent More Helping My Friends in Prison Than in Harrods\u201d|first=Ciaran|last=Thapar|date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Rashid Kasirye of [[Link Up TV]] described Ratlin's song \"Messiah\" as a turning point for the company as numerous bookings started coming into the company as a video director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/10/rashid-kasirye-link-up-tv-interview|title=How Rashid Kasirye\u2019s Link Up TV Became A Dominant Force In UK Rap|website=Complex}}</ref>\n\n[[Fredo (rapper)|Fredo]] was a young member of the Harrow Road Boyz under Ratlin and Rugrat, and initially, he\u2019d never tried rapping, however when he saw rival gangs rapping and their lyrical content, he began his music career as he felt they weren't authentic, as well as to put the Harrow Road Boyz in the limelight by recording his own songs. He has achieved commercial success with numerous charted singles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/02/fredo-interview|title=UK Rap Star Fredo Isn\u2019t Resting On His Laurels|website=Complex}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2020, Muscle Gotti passed away in a car crash in Wembley. He was involved in a police chase.<ref>https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/02/uk-rapper-muscle-gotti-dies-car-accident-12500936/</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n===\u00a3R===\nThe Harrow Road Boyz and gang members of the Mozart Estate have been in an ongoing rivalry with nearby [[hip hop music|hip hop]] [[musical collective|collective]] and gang \u00a3R who's most successful artist is C Biz.<ref name=\"Gang\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/davehillblog/2012/mar/01/youth-violence-london-westminster-brent|title=London falling: violence, feuds and fear scar the capital's heart|first=Dave|last=Hill|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-148377901/be-brave-plea-over-gun-killer-in-brief|title='Be Brave' Plea over Gun Killer; in Brief\" - The Evening Standard (London, England), July 19, 2006 - Online Research Library: Questia Reader|website=Questia.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialaffairsunit.org.uk/blog/archives/001062.php|title=The Social Affairs Unit - Web Review: The Murder of Toni-Ann Byfield: if future such cases are to be prevented the practice of bringing young children into the UK to be educated / exploited in a welfare-rich country must be challenged, argues Lilian Pizzichini|website=www.socialaffairsunit.org.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gangWar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/innocent-queen-s-park-electrician-was-gunned-down-in-revenge-for-gangland-murder-of-south-kilburn-man-1-1403791|title=Innocent Queen's Park electrician was gunned down in revenge for gangland murder of South Kilburn man|first=Ben|last=Bloom|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> This has resulted in numerous shootings, stabbings and [[kidnapping]]s amongst the groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2013/08/westminster-you-dont-see|title=The Westminster you don\u2019t see|website=Newstatesman.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Gang\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-15126415|title='Postcode' wars blighting estate|first=Kevin|last=Young|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"gangWar\" /> The rivalry has been described as to be a typical \"postcode war\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-15126415|title='Postcode' wars blighting estate|first=Kevin|last=Young|date=September 30, 2011|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> as South Kilburn is part of NW6 while Mozart Estate is in W9 and in the [[City of Westminster]].\n\n===1011/CGM===\nHarrow Road Boyz and gang members of the Mozart estate have also been in conflict with members of the 1011/CGM gang and [[hip hop collective]], from the [[Portobello Road|Portobello]] area of [[Ladbroke Grove]]. This is another Postcode war as 1011 are from postcodes [[W postcode area|W10]] and [[W postcode area|W11]] hence the name. The most successful members of 1011 are Digga D, SavO, TY and Horrid1, the former 3 featuring in 1011s \"Next Up\" music video, one of the most watched drill music videos of 2018.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:English hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Hip hop collectives]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from the London Borough of Brent]]\n[[Category:Underground rappers]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2009]]\n[[Category:London street gangs]]\n\n{{UK-band-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = HRB\n| image               = HarrowRoadBoyz_logo.png\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Queen's Park, London|Queen's Park]], [[London]], England\n| genre               = [[British hip hop]]\n| years_active        = 2010\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| current_members     = [[Fredo (rapper)|Fredo]]<br>Ratlin<br>Rugrat<br>Mystro<br>Grizly<br>Rebellion<br>Belly<br>Jah Vinci\n| past_members        = Muscle Gotti (deceased)<ref>https://www.mylondon.news/news/west-london-news/man-being-chased-police-wembley-18034085</ref>\n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Harrow Road Boyz (HRB)''', also referred to as the '''Mozart gang''', is a British [[hip hop music|hip hop]] [[Musical collective|collective]] and [[street gang]] from [[Queen's Park, London|Queen's Park]], [[London]]. Most members of the group are from the notorious Mozart Estate located between Queens Park and [[Ladbroke Grove]].\n\n==History==\nThe name 'Mozart' refers to the gangs territory, the Mozart estate between Ladbroke Grove and Queens Park. One of the earliest members out of the gang who started rapping was '''Ratlin''' (born July 20, 1990). Ratlin's commercial success came with the mixtape ''Youngest In Charge'' which was released in August, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.datpiff.com/RATLIN-CORLEONE-Youngest-In-Charge-mixtape.238789.html|title=Youngest In Charge Mixtape by RATLIN CORLEONE Hosted by MYKA MILLION|website=www.datpiff.com}}</ref> He has since released numerous mixtapes including ''Summertime In Mexico'' and its sequel ''Summertime In Mexico 2'' both of which have accumulated over one million views on YouTube. Ratlin used to play for the local football team [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at 11.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/a3bvnk/fredo-third-avenue-album-interview-2019|title=Fredo: \u201cI\u2019ve Spent More Helping My Friends in Prison Than in Harrods\u201d|first=Ciaran|last=Thapar|date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Rashid Kasirye of [[Link Up TV]] described Ratlin's song \"Messiah\" as a turning point for the company as numerous bookings started coming into the company as a video director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/10/rashid-kasirye-link-up-tv-interview|title=How Rashid Kasirye\u2019s Link Up TV Became A Dominant Force In UK Rap|website=Complex}}</ref>\n\n[[Fredo (rapper)|Fredo]] was a young member of the Harrow Road Boyz under Ratlin and Rugrat, and initially, he\u2019d never tried rapping, however when he saw rival gangs rapping and their lyrical content, he began his music career as he felt they weren't authentic, as well as to put the Harrow Road Boyz in the limelight by recording his own songs. He has achieved commercial success with numerous charted singles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/02/fredo-interview|title=UK Rap Star Fredo Isn\u2019t Resting On His Laurels|website=Complex}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2020, Muscle Gotti passed away in a car crash in Wembley. He was involved in a police chase.<ref>https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/02/uk-rapper-muscle-gotti-dies-car-accident-12500936/</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n===\u00a3R===\nThe Harrow Road Boyz and gang members of the Mozart Estate have been in an ongoing rivalry with nearby [[hip hop music|hip hop]] [[musical collective|collective]] and gang [[\u00a3R]] who's most successful artist is C Biz.<ref name=\"Gang\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/davehillblog/2012/mar/01/youth-violence-london-westminster-brent|title=London falling: violence, feuds and fear scar the capital's heart|first=Dave|last=Hill|date=1 March 2012|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-148377901/be-brave-plea-over-gun-killer-in-brief|title='Be Brave' Plea over Gun Killer; in Brief\" - The Evening Standard (London, England), July 19, 2006 - Online Research Library: Questia Reader|website=Questia.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialaffairsunit.org.uk/blog/archives/001062.php|title=The Social Affairs Unit - Web Review: The Murder of Toni-Ann Byfield: if future such cases are to be prevented the practice of bringing young children into the UK to be educated / exploited in a welfare-rich country must be challenged, argues Lilian Pizzichini|website=www.socialaffairsunit.org.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gangWar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/news/crime-court/innocent-queen-s-park-electrician-was-gunned-down-in-revenge-for-gangland-murder-of-south-kilburn-man-1-1403791|title=Innocent Queen's Park electrician was gunned down in revenge for gangland murder of South Kilburn man|first=Ben|last=Bloom|website=Kilburn Times|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> This has resulted in numerous shootings, stabbings and [[kidnapping]]s amongst the groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2013/08/westminster-you-dont-see|title=The Westminster you don\u2019t see|website=Newstatesman.com|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Gang\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-15126415|title='Postcode' wars blighting estate|first=Kevin|last=Young|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=19 May 2019|website=Bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"gangWar\" /> The rivalry has been described as to be a typical \"postcode war\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-15126415|title='Postcode' wars blighting estate|first=Kevin|last=Young|date=September 30, 2011|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> as South Kilburn is part of NW6 while Mozart Estate is in W9 and in the [[City of Westminster]].\n\n===1011/CGM===\nHarrow Road Boyz and gang members of the Mozart estate have also been in conflict with members of the 1011/CGM gang and [[hip hop collective]], from the [[Portobello Road|Portobello]] area of [[Ladbroke Grove]]. This is another Postcode war as 1011 are from postcodes [[W postcode area|W10]] and [[W postcode area|W11]] hence the name. The most successful members of 1011 are Digga D, SavO, TY and Horrid1, the former 3 featuring in 1011s \"Next Up\" music video, one of the most watched drill music videos of 2018.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:English hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Hip hop collectives]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from the London Borough of Brent]]\n[[Category:Underground rappers]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2009]]\n[[Category:London street gangs]]\n\n{{UK-band-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Yunshui", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/\u00a3Rclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harrow_Road_Boyz"}
{"title_page": "The Clark Sisters", "text_new": "{{About|the gospel group|the 1950s vocal group also known as \"The Clark Sisters\"|The Sentimentalists}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name            = The Clark Sisters\n| image           =\n| caption         = The Clark Sisters at The 50th Annual Grammy Awards\n| alias           = The Dynamic Clark Sisters (1980)\n\nThe Legendary Clark Sisters (2017-Present)\n| origin          = [[Detroit, Michigan]], U.S.\n| genre           = [[Gospel music|Gospel]], [[urban contemporary gospel]]\n| years_active    = 1966\u2013present\n| label           = Billmo, [[Sound Of Gospel]], [[Westbound Records|Westbound]]/[[Elektra Records|Elektra]], [[Rejoice Records|Rejoice]]/[[Word Records|Word]], [[Sparrow Records|Sparrow]], [[EMI Gospel]] Karew\n| associated_acts = [[Mattie Moss Clark]], [[Bill Moss (musician)|Bill Moss, Sr.]], [[Kierra Sheard]], [[J Moss]], [[Bill Moss, Jr.]]\n| website         = {{URL|theclarksisters.net}}\n| current_members = * [[Twinkie Clark|Elbernita \"Twinkie\" Clark]]\n* [[Jacky Clark Chisholm]]\n* [[Dorinda Clark Cole]]\n* [[Karen Clark Sheard]]\n| past_members    = * Denise Clark Bradford\n| background      = group_or_band\n}}\n\n'''The Clark Sisters''' are an American [[gospel music|gospel]] vocal group consisting of five sisters: [[Jacky Clark Chisholm]] (b. 1948), Denise Clark Bradford (b. 1953), [[Twinkie Clark|Elbernita \"Twinkie\" Clark]] (b. 1954), [[Dorinda Clark-Cole]] (b. 1957), and [[Karen Clark Sheard]] (b. 1960). The Clark Sisters are the daughters of gospel musician and choral director Dr. [[Mattie Moss Clark]]. They are credited for helping to bring gospel music to the mainstream and are considered as pioneers of contemporary gospel. Their biggest hits include: \"Is My Living in Vain\", \"Hallelujah\", \"He Gave Me Nothing to Lose\", \"Endow Me\", \"Jesus Is A Love Song\", \"Ha-Ya (Eternal Life)\", \"Pure Gold\", \"Expect Your Miracle\", and their largest mainstream crossover gold-certified hit, \"You Brought the Sunshine\". The Clark Sisters have won three<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=%22The+Clark+Sisters%22&field_nominee_work_value=&year=All&genre=All&=Search|title=Past Winners Search|work=The GRAMMYs|access-date=October 5, 2014}}</ref> [[Grammy Awards]]. With 17 albums to their credit and millions in sales, the Clark Sisters are the highest-selling female gospel group in history.\n\n==History==\n\n=== The early years ===\nThe Clark Sisters were born and raised in Detroit, Michigan to world-renowned gospel choir director and musician Dr. Mattie Moss Clark. Dr. Clark was married twice: her first marriage in 1945 to Leo H. Cullum, Sr. produced two children, Leo, Jr. and Jacqueline (Jacky).  After her divorce, she met and later married Pastor Elbert Clark in 1952. This marriage produced four daughters: Denise, Elbernita (Twinkie), Dorinda, and Karen. They each began singing at an early age in the choir at their father's church, and by the late 1960s they were all performing together in church services, usually singing songs written and arranged by their mother. Shortly after the Clarks' divorce in 1973, Dr. Clark formally created \"the Clark Sisters\" and the sisters recorded their first album, ''Jesus Has A Lot To Give'', on their uncle (their mother's younger brother) [[Bill Moss (musician)|Bill Moss]]' local label Billesse Records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jlentertainment.com/artistbio.cfm?artistname=The%20Clark%20Sisters|title=The Clark Sisters Biography|publisher=JLEntertainment.com}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, ''Dr. Mattie Moss Clark Presents the Clark Sisters'' was released and people around Detroit began to take notice of the group. The Clark Sisters signed to Sound of Gospel Records in 1974. Under this association, the group released albums such as ''Unworthy'', ''Count It All Joy'', and ''[[He Gave Me Nothing to Lose]]''. By this point, Dr. Clark had turned over control of the group to Twinkie, who continued to write, arrange, conduct, and produce all of the Clark Sisters' recordings. It was not until the early 1980s that the Clark Sisters began to become more widely known.{{Peacock-term|date=December 2011}} Their popularity soared with the release of the live recording ''Is My Living In Vain''. The first live recording by the Clark Sisters spent an entire year at number one on Billboard's Gospel Music chart.{{citation needed |date=September 2013}} Opening with the bluesy title track, each sister vocally declares that their dedication to Christ is not a useless effort. The innovative \"Ha-Ya (Eternal Life)\" was funky enough to find its way into a Tonex produced track over two decades later. Karen Clark's lead on \"Speak Lord\" expresses deep faith while the call to worship is raised on \"Now Is The Time\". Another hit from this release, \"Expect Your Miracle\", is still a staple in African American churches across the country.<ref name=\"theclarksisters.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.theclarksisters.com/discography.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110045508/http://www.theclarksisters.com/discography.html |archivedate=January 10, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nTheir next release ''[[You Brought the Sunshine]]'' would prove to be a monster hit via the title track. Reminiscent of [[Stevie Wonder]]'s \"[[Master Blaster (Jammin')]],\" the song became a hit in churches and on dance floors, including New York's [[Studio 54]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prayzehymnonline.com/articles_80scountdown.html|title=80's Countdown|publisher=PraiseHymnOnline.com|author=J. Matthew Cobb|date=August 31, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070318004026/http://www.prayzehymnonline.com/articles_80scountdown.html|archivedate=March 18, 2007}}</ref> \"Sunshine\" was picked up from its original independent gospel record label Sounds of Gospel and distributed by both Westbound Records and Elektra Records. In 1983, the song peaked at #16 on the Black Singles chart, #27 on the Club Play Charts, and #80 on the Hot R&B Charts<ref>{{Cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p2239/charts-awards/billboard-singles|pure_url=yes}}|title=The Clark Sisters Chart History|publisher=Allmusic}}</ref> driving the album to Gold sales. This album continues to display Twinkie's signature blend of scripture with unprecedented vocal and musical arrangements on biblically based songs like \"Psalms 31.\" The album's other songs include the sincere prayer found within the lyrics of both \"Center of Thy Will\" and \"Endow Me,\" featuring a young but already vocally mature Karen, as well as \"Overdose of the Holy Ghost\", showcasing Dorinda's vocal dexterity. The disco-inspired \"He Keeps Me Company\" is noted for its bubbly syncopation.<ref name=\"theclarksisters.com\"/>\n\nThe sisters delivered another progressive effort in 1982, ''Sincerely'', which included \"Name It, Claim It\" and the politically charged \"World.\" Though its success was overshadowed by the previous hit \"You Brought the Sunshine\", the album received a Grammy Award nomination.<ref name=\"theclarksisters.com\"/>\n\n===More success===\nIn 1986, after a four-year gap between releases, the sisters: Jacky, Twinkie, Dorinda, and Karen (sister Denise left the group earlier that year) continued to release music, signing with [[Rejoice Records]], a division of [[Word Records|Word]].  This new deal yielded the Grammy-nominated ''Heart & Soul'' featuring the mainstream single \"Time Out\". This project made a top 5 debut on Billboard's Gospel Charts and garnered the group a coveted Dove Award. It featured the original versions of \"Jesus is a Love Song\", \"There is a Balm in Gilead\", and \"Pray for the USA\", which has been re-recorded several times. Although not pictured, Denise had contributed to the album before her departure. The music took on a more contemporary sound with programmed drums and synthesizers. Also included on this album were \"Smile, God Loves You\", \"Time Out\", \"I Am Blessed\", and the funky \"He\u2019ll Turn Your Scars Into Stars.\"<ref name=\"theclarksisters.com\"/>\n\nIn 1988, the Clark Sisters released their Billboard chart-topping and critically acclaimed album ''Conqueror''. It featured a bolder, more intense sound, with synthesizers, drum machines and more funk-oriented beats. ''Conqueror'' quickly became a fan favorite with hits like \"The Darkest Hour is Just Before the Day\", \"Take Me Higher\", \"For the Love of the People\", \"Computers Rule the World\", and the original studio version of \"Jesus Forevermore\".<ref name=\"theclarksisters.com\"/>\n\nIn 1989, the Clark Sisters released their highly anticipated live album, ''Bringing it Back Home'', recorded in their home town of Detroit. It was the last recording from the Clark Sisters on Word Records\u2019 Rejoice imprint and the last group album with Twinkie just before the launch of her solo career. The album included both previous hits and new material. It featured guest appearances from gospel icon [[Rance Allen]] and backing choir vocals from the Michigan State Choir under the direction of their mother, Dr. Mattie Moss Clark.<ref name=\"theclarksisters.com\"/>\n\nIn 1994, the Clark Sisters released their last studio album before breaking grounds into their successful solo careers. Their last studio album of the decade, ''Miracle'', was the first album the Clark Sisters recorded without the songwriting and vocals of sister Twinkie. Produced by [[BeBe Winans]] & [[Michael J. Powell]], this disc features a very pop version of the Clark Sisters classic \"Expect Your Miracle\" (now titled \"Miracle\") and a remake of the classic \"Jesus is The Best Thing\". Dorinda made her songwriting debut on a Clark Sisters recording with \"Work to Do\". That album, although it fared well in sales, did not match the success of previous albums due to the Clark Sisters not being able to tour and promote the project, due to the illness of their mother, Dr. Mattie Moss Clark, who died in September 1994 from diabetes complications.<ref name=\"theclarksisters.com\"/>\n\n===Emerging solo artists===\nFollowing their last Word Records release, Twinkie resumed her calling as a minister and her solo career. She had previously released two solo albums under the Sound of Gospel Record label: 1979's ''Praise Belongs to God'' and 1981's ''Ye Shall Receive Power'', both of which have become classics.  In 1992 she recorded her independent solo album ''Comin' Home''.  She re-appeared in 1996 with a pair of albums to her credit: the solo studio release ''The Masterpiece'' for [[Ben Tankard]]'s [[Tribute Records]] label and the live project ''Twinkie Clark-Terrell Presents the Florida A&M University Gospel Choir''.  She later released the following albums: ''Twinkie Clark & Friends: Live in Charlotte'' in 2002, ''Home Once Again: Live in Detroit'' in 2004, ''With Humility'' in 2011, ''Live & Unplugged'' in 2015, and with her nephew Larry Clark (her sister Denise's oldest son) ''The Generations'' in 2020. \n\nKaren delivered her solo debut ''[[Finally Karen (album)|Finally Karen]]'' in 1997. The album, featuring star turns from the Clark Sisters, [[Faith Evans]], and daughter [[Kierra Sheard]], was nominated for a Grammy Award, in addition to winning a [[Soul Train Lady of Soul Award|Soul Train Lady of Soul]] award. She has since released five more solo albums: ''[[2nd Chance (Karen Clark Sheard album)|2nd Chance]]'', ''[[The Heavens Are Telling (album)|The Heavens Are Telling]]'', ''[[It's Not Over (Karen Clark Sheard album)|It's Not Over]]'', ''[[All in One (Karen Clark Sheard album)|All in One]], and [[Destined to Win]]. ''\n\nDorinda released her self-titled debut solo album, [[Dorinda Clark-Cole]] in 2002, earning her two [[Stellar Awards]], and a Soul Train Lady of Soul award. She has since released four more solo albums: ''Live in Houston'' and ''Take It Back'', each of which have earned her the award for Female Vocalist of the Year at the Stellar Awards; ''I Survived'' in 2011, and in 2015, she released her fifth solo album, ''Living It'', which was nominated for a Grammy Award for Best Gospel Album. \n\nJacky released her first solo project, ''Expectancy'', in 2005, which features the Clark Sisters on the track \"Blessing Me.\" In 2014, she released an urban inspired single \u201cMy Season\u201d followed by singles \u201cCover Me\u201d and \u201cShout\u201d. In February 2020, she released a single \"Feel Good\", featuring Mary J. Blige and rapper Tia P.\n\nThe Clark Sisters have all contributed in various capacities to each other's albums, whether they sang or wrote lyrics.\n\n===Live...One Last Time===\nOn July 8, 2006, the Clark Sisters (Jacky, Twinkie, Dorinda, and Karen) recorded a live album in [[Houston, Texas]] entitled ''Live...One Last Time''.  The recording was directed and produced by [[Donald Lawrence]] and was released as a [[CD]] on April 10, 2007<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theclarksisters.com/whatsnew.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-02-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070213174605/http://www.theclarksisters.com/whatsnew.htm |archivedate=February 13, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> on EMI Gospel, followed by a CD/DVD Special Edition release June 19, 2007. In support of the reunion album, the Clark Sisters embarked on a 25-city concert tour beginning October 4, 2007 in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]].<ref>[http://www.gospelcity.com/news/events/379 The Clark Sisters Concert Tour] GospelCity.com.</ref> Though they had been thrice nominated previously for the [[Grammy Award for Best Soul Gospel Performance by a Duo or Group, Choir or Chorus|Best Soul Gospel Performance by a Duo or Group]] Grammy with 1982's ''Sincerely'', 1986's ''Heart & Soul'', and 1988's ''Conqueror'' without a win,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/factsheets/awardsdb/env-awards-db-search,0,7169155.htmlstory?selectsearch=awardsdb&target=article&searchtype=all&Query=Clark+Sisters|title=Awards Database|publisher=The Envelope}}</ref> the group won three Grammys in 2008. ''Live...One Last Time'' won the award for [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Soul Gospel Album|Best Traditional Gospel Album]]. Its album track \"Blessed & Highly Favored\" won the award for [[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Performance|Best Gospel Performance]], and as songwriter of \"Blessed & Highly Favored,\" sister Karen Clark Sheard won the individual award for [[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Song|Best Gospel Song]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.grammy.org/GRAMMY_Awards/50th_Show/list.aspx|title=50th Annual Grammy Awards Nomination List|publisher=Grammy.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/50th_show/list.aspx|title=50th Annual Grammy Awards Nomination List|publisher=Grammy.org}}</ref> Additionally, at the [[50th Annual Grammy Awards]] ceremony featuring a gospel segment with [[Aretha Franklin]], [[BeBe Winans]], [[Israel & New Breed]], and [[Trin-i-tee 5:7]], the Clark Sisters performed a snippet of their signature hit \"You Brought the Sunshine\" when the ceremony was broadcast on February 10 at the [[Staples Center]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1046733/beyonce-rihanna-underwood-performing-at-grammys|title=Beyonce, Rihanna, Underwood Performing At Grammys|publisher=Billboard.com|date=January 24, 2008|author=Mariel Concepcion}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the group's resurgence in popularity, [[Rhino Entertainment]] released a greatest-hits collection including material from three albums recorded for Word Records from the mid-1980s through the early 1990s, including the Grammy-nominated ''Heart & Soul''. The album, ''[[Encore (Clark Sisters album)|Encore: The Best of The Clark Sisters]]'', was released February 12, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuthinbutgospel.com/newreleases.htm|title=NuthinButGospel.com New Releases 2008|publisher=|accessdate=October 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0011B9W1A Encore: The Best of The Clark Sisters] on [[Amazon.com]]</ref> In December of that year, [[TV One (American TV channel)|TV One]]'s popular hour-long music documentary series [[Unsung (TV series)|Unsung]] featured the Clark Sisters in an episode. The episode, which highlighted the group's role in breaking down barriers in Gospel music, featured interviews with each sister except sister Denise Clark Bradford, who since leaving the group, relocated to California and began a ministry.\n\nIn 2009, the Clark Sisters released their second Christmas album, entitled ''The Clark Sisters' Family Christmas'', which featured special appearances by Karen's daughter Kierra Sheard, and their cousins Bill Moss, Jr. and James Moss (known as [[J. Moss]]).  The album was produced by Karen's son, J. Drew Sheard, II.\n\n===Lifetime Movie and New Music===\nOn November 11, 2018, It was reported that the Clark Sisters would have a television biopic, ''[[The Clark Sisters: First Ladies of Gospel]].'' The film aired on [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] on April 11, 2020. The film is executive produced by [[Queen Latifah]], [[Missy Elliott]], and [[Mary J. Blige]], and will star [[Aunjanue Ellis]] as Dr. [[Mattie Moss Clark]], Angela Birchett as [[Jacky Clark Chisholm]], [[Raven Goodwin]] as Denise Clark Bradford, Christina Bell as [[Twinkie Clark]], [[Shel\u00e9a|Shel\u00e9a Frazier]] as [[Dorinda Clark Cole]], and [[Kierra Sheard]] as her mother, [[Karen Clark Sheard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/entertainment/clark-sisters-biopic-queen-latifah-mary-j-blige-missy-elliott-lifetime-2019/|title=Clark Sisters Biopic Produced By Queen Latifah, Mary J. Blige And Missy Elliott Coming In 2019}}</ref> The script was written by Camille Tucker, with a teleplay by Sylvia L. Jones, and Christine Swanson directing.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Clark Sisters: The First Ladies of Gospel|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt10098482/|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed the Clark Sisters among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2019, the Clark Sisters debuted their new single \"Victory\" on [[Erica Campbell]]'s radio show \"Get Up Erica\".<ref>{{Citation|title=EXCLUSIVE: The Clark Sisters Debut \u201cVictory\u201d Single, Discuss Making Of Upcoming Biopic [AUDIO]|url=https://getuperica.com/126161/the-clark-sisters-new-music-biopic/|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref> The single was later released on November 15, 2019 through [[Karew Records|Karew]]/[[Motown|Motown Gospel]]/[[Capitol Records|Capitol CMG]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Victory - Sing by The Clark Sisters on Apple Music|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/victory-single/1485815391|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> On March 13, 2020, the Clark Sisters released their seventeenth album, ''The Return''. Their first release in over a decade, features production from J. Drew Sheard, II, [[Warryn Campbell|Warryn Campell]], [[Rodney Jerkins]], [[Jermaine Dupri]], Mano Hines, and [[Kurt Carr]], with a special feature by [[Snoop Dogg]] on the track, \"His Love\".\n\n==\"The Clark Sound\"==\nThe Clark Sisters are renowned for their vocal stylings, dubbed as \"the Clark Sound.\" They incorporate high and fast [[melisma]]s, acrobatic [[trill (music)|trills]] and [[riffs]], and deep, soulful [[growling|growls]], or \"squalls\". The sisters are also known for the individual distinctive sounds that they contribute. Jacky ([[alto]]/[[tenor]]) is known for her sweet, soft, smooth, and deeper vocals. Dorinda ([[alto]]/[[mezzo-soprano]]), the \"jazzy\" sister, inputs [[Scat singing|scats]], riffs, and runs with a fervency that places her in a class of her own. She has an innate ability to make each song her very own and she is a preacher to be reckoned with. Denise ([[soprano]]) was known for her high pitched, youthful singing voice and used her piercing soprano vocals, which are clearly heard on the group's first ten albums. She was also known for her runs and high melismas. Karen([[soprano]]) is known for her unique riffs, runs, growls, scats, very vast vocal range, ability to belt whilst in the whistle range, and has also been known to implement an \"echo\" in her live performances. Twinkie, credited with being \"the Heart of the Clark Sisters\", is known for her complex runs, riffs, powerful mixed-voice belts, soulful squalls, deep growls, and large vocal range spanning from high soprano to baritone--a range very few women have. One of the highest notes recorded by Twinkie came in one of the songs she penned, \u201cThe Darkest Hour is Just Before the Day\u201d, hitting a powerful F6 (an F in the 6th octave). Early in the group's development, Twinkie was the chief songwriter, music and vocal arranger, and producer.\n\nThere is no single lead vocalist in the group. Jacky leads songs such as \"Wonderful Counselor,\" \"I've Got An Angel,\" \"So Much Joy\", and \"God Understands All\". Dorinda leads \"Overdose of the Holy Ghost,\" \"Time Out\", \"My Redeemer Liveth\", \"I Won't Let Go 'Til You Bless My Soul\", \"Determination\", \"Looking To Get There (Heaven)\", and \"Sanctify Me Lord\".  Karen sings lead on \"A Praying Spirit\", \"Hallelujah,\" \"Endow Me,\" and the Grammy-winning \"Blessed and Highly Favored.\" Twinkie leads on \"Nothing to Lose\", \"Expect Your Miracle\", \"Pray for the USA,\" \"I've Got The Victory\", and their biggest hit \"You Brought the Sunshine.\" Denise sings lead on \"Who Can I Turn To\", \"Something Worth Living For\", \"Count it All Joy\", and \"Christ is Born Today.\" She co-leads with her sister Twinkie on \"Holiness\" and \"Hark The Herald Angels Sing,\" and also with her sister Dorinda on the original version of \u201cThere Is a Balm In Gilead\u201d performed on local television shows, at concerts, and at Convocations before it was recorded on their album.\n\nThe group's sound and success have been highly influential on the contemporary genre of gospel music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theclarksisters.emigospel.com/news/|title=Lost redirect|publisher=|accessdate=October 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of albums, with selected chart positions, sales figures and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:21em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard charts|US<br>Gospel]]<br><ref name=\"Gospel Albums\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/the-clark-sisters/chart-history/SLL|title=The Clark Sisters Chart History: Top Gospel Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard charts|US<br>Christian]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/the-clark-sisters/chart-history/ILL|title=The Clark Sisters Chart History: Top Christian Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''Jesus Has a Lot to Give''\n|style=\"font-size:12px;\"|\n* Released: 1973\n* Label: Bilesse Records <small>(#BM 354)</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/The-Clark-Sisters-Jesus-Has-A-Lot-To-Give-/release/7131011|title=The Clark Sisters \u200e\u2013 Jesus Has A Lot To Give (1973, Vinyl)|accessdate=April 21, 2020|website=[[Discogs]]}}</ref>\n* Formats: [[L